<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FloridaLottery     04-30 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Lottery,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>859 People, One Newspaper Have Winning Florida Lottery Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The St. Petersburg Times had a winning
ticket but no winners in the fledgling Florida lottery's first
computerized numbers game.
   A photo at the top of the front page of Friday morning's
newspaper showed the numbers 8-0-6, which turned out to be the
winning combination in the first Cash 3 contest that night. The
photo, used to illustrate a story about the lottery, was of a
sample ticket sent to the paper a month ago.
   ``This was entirely coincidental,'' City Editor Jack Reed said.
``It doesn't seem like that should need to be said, but we've
gotten so many calls.''
   The first daily contest produced 859 winners but none in the
Times newsroom.
   ``In fact, I don't know anyone that played daily game in the
newsroom,'' Reed said.
   A spokesman for the lottery said the first Cash 3 game drawing
went off without a hitch. Pingpong balls with the winning numbers
were selected in only 60 seconds. The payout totaled $94,090.
   Ticket sales are expected to top $10 million in the first week.
By 7:30 p.m. Friday, $616,543 had been wagered on Cash 3 and
$345,377 on the jackpot Lotto game. Thirty-five percent of all
lottery revenues are earmarked for public education.
   The first Lotto drawing will be held May 7. The prize will be at
least $2 million but could reach $4 million.
   Florida joins 27 other states and the District of Columbia that
have legalized lotteries. Law enforcement officials hope the
legalized Florida numbers games will help undermine illegal numbers
rackets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
