<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-YouthCrime     04-30 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Youth Crime,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juveniles Cause Two-Thirds of Crimes in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Juveniles cause more than 60 percent of the crime
in China the crimes they commit are becoming more violent, the
official China Daily reported today.
   The newspaper quoted Xu Jian, vice president of China Research
Association of Juvenile Delinquency, as saying the rate of juvenile
crime is 12 per 10,000 of the same age group.
   He said that was more than double the overall crime rate of 5
per 10,000 people, but still much lower than in developed countries.
   Xu gave no figures for juvenile crimes or what age group is
classified as juveniles.
   He said youths who in the past mainly committed minor offenses
such as petty thefts and fighting are now engaged in robberies,
violent assaults and rapes. Xu attributed the rise in juvenile
crime to the lack of proper laws, the spread of pornography, the
increasing numbers of working parents and divorce.
   Girls, mainly involved in hooliganism _ a general term for
unsocial behavior _ or sex crimes, made up 18.6 percent of juvenile
criminals in 1985, up from 10 percent in 1983, he said.
   Xu said juvenile delinquency would continue to rise in the near
future and called for a national network to educate and prevent
youths from committing crimes.
</TEXT>
