<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseSpending 610   04-30 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Spending, 610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Rejects Threat Of Pullout To Increase Allied Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House says the Reagan administration ought
to talk with NATO countries and Japan about spending more for
defense, but has rejected calls to bring American troops home if
that isn't done.
   The decisions were part of the Democratic-controlled House's
effort to write a Pentagon budget bill for the fiscal year starting
Oct. 1.
   The House voted 359-0 late Friday afternoon to approve a
proposal calling for the administration to initiate talks with
Japan and NATO member nations about sharing the burden for defense.
   The House vote came as the Pentagon released its 1988 report on
``Allied Contributions to the Common Defense,'' an annual
assessment mandated by Congress.
   The report was accompanied by a personal pledge from Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci to ``press at every opportunity for
progress'' in sharing the burdens of the alliance.
   Carlucci said the report's ``principal conclusion'' is that the
allies are making more of a contribution than they receive credit
for, but he said ``there are substantial variations in performance
among individual allies.''
   The House vote echoed a similar proposal approved last summer by
Congress, but the administration hasn't yet pushed hard for the
talks.
   Both House and Senate members have criticized Western Europe and
Japan for failing to spend more on defense. They note that the
United States spends about 6.9 percent of its gross national
product on defense, a far larger share than other western nations.
   Despite the criticism, Congress has refused for three years to
order sanctions against Japan and the alliance, a refusal that was
continued Friday by the House.
   The United States has about 326,000 troops stationed in Europe
and 63,000 in Japan.
   By a 240-120 vote, the House rejected a proposal by Rep. John
Bryant, D-Texas, to bring 30,000 troops a year back from Europe and
7,000 troops a year from Japan starting in 1991.
   Minutes later it voted 332-21 to reject a plan by Rep. Tommy
Robinson, D-Ark., to withdraw 70,000 troops a year from Europe.
   ``Let's get smart and begin to tell our allies that we expect
them to pay their fair share,'' Bryant said. ``We are subsidizing
their defense.''
   Robinson made a similar appeal, telling his colleagues: ``The
real purpose of this amendment is to demonstrate to our allies that
we've had it. These people are stealing our jobs because we have
been suckered into paying for their defense.''
   But Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., said the issue should be
``considered in a clear process and not on an emotional basis.''
   ``It is simply not possible to maintain the viability of a
voluntary alliance of free countries if one of those countries
tries to impose standards on the others,'' said Rep. Stephen
Solarz, D-N.Y.
   But Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., said, ``It's time Uncle Sam quit
being taken for Uncle Sucker.''
   The spending bill would authorize the Pentagon to spend $299.5
billion in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, which is the same
amount proposed by the separate bill that will be considered next
month by the Senate. Differences between the bills eventually will
be reconciled by a House-Senate conference committee.
   The Pentagon report said that the 6.1 percent of gross national
product spent by Greece for defense in 1986 was the closest to the
U.S. share.
   England was third with 5.1 percent, followed by Turkey at 4.8
percent and France at 3.9 percent.
   ``All of the remaining nations have shares of 3.2 percent or
less,'' the study found.
   The report used 1986 data because that is the most recent year
for which figures were available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
