<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OSHA-WarningTags     04-30 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OSHA-Warning Tags,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Issues Long-Awaited Regulations On Idled Machinery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Occupational Safety and Health
Administration wants employers to put warning tags on machinery
that has been shut off to prevent injuries and deaths caused when
the machines are turned on while being cleaned or serviced.
   Nine years and 1,000 deaths after unions first pleaded for
action on one of the single biggest causes of industrial accidents,
the agency issued proposed regulations Friday on so-called
``tagouts'' and ``lockouts.''
   The proposals appeared in the Federal Register a week after
Senate Labor Committee Chairman Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said
the delay showed the Reagan administration's ``decision to let
workers die while waiting on a standard.''
   OSHA officials testified last week at a Senate hearing chaired
by Kennedy that the proposed regulations had been completed by the
agency in early 1987 but had languished at the White House for
nearly a year.
   About 7 percent of all occupational fatalities and 2 per cent of
accident-caused injuries in the workplace occur now because such
equipment is inadvertently restarted while someone is working on it.
   The agency estimated Friday that the so-called
``performance-oriented'' regulations will save 122 lives and
prevent 60,000 job injuries a year. But they would require
employers only to follow certain steps in turning off equipment and
``minimize'' the potential for inadvertently reactivating it.
   ``Very simple lockout, tagout measures, which taken only a few
minutes, can prevent up to 10 percent of all the serious injuries
in some major manufacturing industries,'' said Assistant Labor
Secretary John A. Pendergrass.
   Agency officials estimated it will be a minimum of another year
before the regulations are actually enacted.
   Unions had begun petitioning the agency for the regulations in
1979.
   John Molovich, a safety specialist for the United Steelworkers
Union, predicted employers will ignore the guidelines and ``take
the cheapest way out'' by using cardboard warning tags instead of
locks to prevent a machine from being turned on.
   ``There will be no positive means of assuring that the equipment
won't start,'' he said.
   The regulations, if adopted in current form, will apply to only
1.6 million employers and cover only 39 million workers, most of
them in manufacturing. OSHA estimated the annual cost of compliance
to businesses at $135 million.
   Exempted are millions of companies and workers in agriculture,
oil and gas drilling, electric utilities, the maritime industry and
construction. OSHA said protections for them will be included in
other regulations to be proposed later.
   James Scully, an OSHA official who worked on the regulations for
more than a decade, testified at the Senate Labor Committee
hearings last week that the agency had first seen a need for them
back in 1977.
   But OSHA took no serious action until 1979, when the United Auto
Workers Union, reacting to the deaths of 22 of its members in
related accidents the previous five years, formally asked the
government for emergency action.
   OSHA denied that request and similar pleas in 1982 and 1986 from
other unions.
</TEXT>
