<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OrganizedCrime     04-30 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Organized Crime,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobster Says ``We Don't Kill Innocent People''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An indicted New York City mobster says La Cosa
Nostra families use murder to enforce their internal rules, but
insists, ``We don't kill innocent people.''
   Vincent ``The Fish'' Cafaro, who was a ``soldier'' in the
Genovese organized crime family, told senators Friday the
organization was ``very disciplined'' and members paid a high price
for breaking the rules.
   ``Killings were mandatory'' for fooling around with another
member's wife and dealing in drugs, he said.
   ``When it comes to an amico nostra's wife or `junk' there was no
talk,'' Cafaro said. An amico nostra is a member of a mob family,
and ``junk'' means narcotics.
   Cafaro said mob members also could get murdered for ``ratting,
refusing to go on a `hit' if asked or knowingly killing a cop or
other law enforcement agent.''
   To win approval to carry out a murder, Cafaro said, mob members
had to go through the chain of command, right up to the boss of the
family.
   But he insisted, ``We don't kill innocent people.''
   Unlike witnesses who spoke from behind a screen, Cafaro _ a
thin, balding man with glasses _ testified in full public view
before the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations.
   He currently is in custody while awaiting trial in New York on
racketeering, extortion and conspiracy charges. After his arrest in
1986, he cooperated with federal authorities and even carried a
concealed microphone while talking to other mobsters.
   But Cafaro said personal safety concerns have persuaded him to
end the effort, and he was heavily guarded in the hearing room.
   ``I'm fair game, no question about it,'' he said.
   Cafaro said he had worked for the mob since 1958, as an
associate of ``Fat Tony'' Salerno, a major figure in the Genovese
family. Salerno, who Cafaro said was ``like a father to me,'' is
now on trial in New York on charges related to mob activities.
   Cafaro also told the committee, headed by Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
that four organized crime families run the high-rise construction
industry in New York City through control over the concrete
industry and construction unions.
   He said bids were rigged, and that contractors and unions
winning construction jobs had to kick back 2 percent of the
contract price to the mob.
   Cafaro said the system was arranged through the ```2 Percent
Club,'' an organization run by the Genovese, Gambino, Lucchese and
Colombo families.
   He estimated that at least 50 percent of the high-rise
construction in New York had a mob connection and added,
``Legitimate guys ain't got a chance'' to win contracts for those
buildings.
   Cafaro said each of the four mob families had an expert on the
construction business in the organization. Members read the Dodge
Reports, a construction trade publication that lists upcoming jobs,
he said.
   ``The club members split up all of the jobs over $2 million,''
he said. But if the contract went over $5 million, it went to a
mob-run company, S & A Concrete, he said.
   When the smaller contractors complained of the arrangement, he
said, they won the right to split all jobs over $3 million.
   As a mob soldier who turned down promotions because he didn't
want the added responsibility, Cafaro said he preferred to run the
numbers business in West Harlem.
   ``I had some bad years, but in a good year I could make as much
as $2 million or more,'' he said.
   When Nunn asked if he kept the money, Cafaro said: ``I spent it.
I gave it away. I loaned a lot of money to people and never got it
back.'' The mobster said he only carried cash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
