<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PromRevival 1stLd-Writethru a0726 04-30 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prom Revival, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0726,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senior Prom Returns after 25-Year Hiatus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with prom under way. PICKS UP
2nd graf pvs, `The last ...'; INSERTS three grafs after 10th graf
pvs, `The town ...' to UPDATE with prom underway.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM PARSONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORREST CITY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senior prom returned to Forrest
City High School on Friday, more than 25 years after it was banned
by school officials.
   ``I'm gonna do Da Bump,'' John Williams, an 18-year-old senior,
said as he made his appearance at the Forrest City Civic Center
dressed all in white but for a black snap-brim hat and black cane.
   The last prom was in 1962, said Principal Oscar Collins, who
helped plan the last one as a senior class sponsor early in his
career.
   He said he didn't know what had prompted the ban _ ``I was just
a teacher at the time'' _ noting that it wouldn't have been a
racial issue because the first black student didn't enter the
school until 1965.
   ``That was before integration. After that, the board voted not
to have them any more,'' Collins said.
   However, the student council officers decided not to have a king
and queen for the new prom partly because the couple might be
racially mixed, the Arkansas Gazette reported Friday.
   The newspaper's assertion was disputed by Kaki Dunn, 17,
recording secretary for the council. ``We decided not to have a
prom king and queen because we feel that we're all kings and
queens,'' she said. ``We talked about it and said, `No, we don't
want to do that.'''
   More than half the 355 seniors were expected to attend the dance
in the Forrest City Civic Center, Student Council President
Tangella Brown said.
   Assistant Principal Tom Bridges said he expected the crowd to be
about evenly divided between black and white students, like the
composition of the 1,450-student school.
   ``I don't think that's even been thought about,'' Bridges said.
   The town of about 14,000, 45 miles west of Memphis, Tenn., is
about evenly divided between black and white.
   The boys wore black, white or gray but the colors of the girls'
gowns ranged across the spectrum and skirt lengths were anywhere
between the ankles and the knees.
   Three couples stepped out of a stretch limouisine from a funeral
home, the driver holding the door. Then, at the request of a TV
crew, they got back in and did it again.
   Jack McNair, 18, sharply dressed in an Army Junior ROTC uniform,
came all the way from Benton, 125 miles to the west, to escort his
cousin, Lori Martin, 18.
   Precautions were taken to avoid any problems at the prom,
Bridges said.
   ``There'll be strictly no drinking,'' he said. ``We don't allow
smoking anyway, at the school, so there'll be no smoking at the
prom, no drinking, no drugs.'' Students who leave the prom will not
be able to return, he said.
   ``And there won't be any press or anything like that,'' Bridges
said. ``It's going to be strictly for the kids.''
   The Forrest City School Board voted last fall to allow the
Student Council to sponsor a prom for 1988's graduating seniors.
   ``We just thought it was time for us to do like other folks,''
school board member Bill Baxter said after that meeting.
   ``It's a milestone,'' said Mayor Danny Ferguson, a 1967 graduate
of the school. ``People in Forrest City are pulling together to
project a positive image.''
   No dances have been sponsored by the school since 1962, not even
informal hops in the gym, Ms. Brown said this week.
   ``They've had them, but they were provided by different
fraternities or different sororities,'' said Ms. Brown, 17, who is
black. ``But as for those provided by the school, this will be the
first.''
   The private dances, Collins said, have been strictly black or
white affairs, none of them integrated.
   The theme chosen for the prom was ``A Night on the Town,'' said
Bridges.
   ``They've got skyscrapers and all that,'' he said. ``It'll look
pretty good.''
</TEXT>
