<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bowen-Drugs     04-30 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bowen-Drugs,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Soft-Pedals Bowen Pessimism On Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary Otis R. Bowen, in a move
acknowledged by the White House to be ``a little unusual,'' is
taking public issue with the assertion that the administration is
winning the war on drugs.
   ``Generally speaking, Mr. President, I prefer optimism to
pessimism, as you do,'' Bowen told Reagan and three Cabinet
colleagues at a meeting of the National Drug Policy Board. ``But
today, I don't know how I can honestly be very optimistic about the
war on drugs.''
   Bowen said Reagan's leadership has resulted in ``major gains.''
   ``We're winning some battles,'' he said, ``but it's difficult
for me to say we're winning the war, especially when we consider
drug dealing and use in our streets and our homes.''
   A text of Bowen's remarks at the private White House meeting on
Thursday was made public Friday by the Department of Health and
Human Services.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged afterward
that it was ``a little unusual'' for a Cabinet officer to go public
with remarks delivered to the president in a private meeting.
   But he sought to soft-pedal any differences between Reagan and
Bowen.
   ``That's the same thing the president said _ we've made progress
but obviously we need to do more,'' said Fitzwater.
   ``I don't know what he's up to,'' Fitzwater said of Bowen's
action. ``On the other hand, there's nothing wrong with it.''
   Reagan often has been upbeat about the war on drugs. ``With all
the headlines about how we're losing the drug war, let's keep in
mind the progress we've made,'' he told a White House Conference
for a Drug-Free America on Feb. 29, adding, ``We've strengthened
the laws'' and ``drug seizures are at an all-time high.''
   Bowen backed the administration's call for tougher law
enforcement in his Thursday presentation, but he also called for
more attention to effective treatment and strong federal leadership
to establish additional treatment clinics.
   And he made clear there was a pragmatic political component to
his appeal.
   ``Mr. President, there are political dangers as well,'' said the
HHS chief.
   In a clear refererence to Jesse Jackson, Bowen said, ``One of
the two remaining Democrat candidates for president is getting some
of his highest marks for his passionate and creative oratory on the
drug epidemic and is poised to steal from our party what has been a
traditional Republican issue _ law enforcement.''
   Bowen supported aggressive law enforcement and other approaches
such as first lady Nancy Reagan's ``Just Say No'' campaign, but he
said ``some'' are using the first lady's campaign ``as a political
football, saying it's an empty slogan, however unfair that
characterization might be.''
   He went on: ``I believe as we approach the end of this second
term, we need to take a fresh look at what we're doing to secure a
lasting end to the demand for illicit drugs.''
   He called for more research to improve the efficiency of
treatment strategies and expanded treatment facilities.
   ``On the topic of treatment,'' Bowen said, ``we also need to
talk turkey with big-city mayors, councils, and suburban
jurisdictions as well, who often knuckle under to pressure from
those who are, quote-unquote, `all for treatment, as long as it's
not in my backyard.'
   ``Communities and neighborhoods need to be willing to accept
treatment facilities,'' he said. ``In some instances, (federal)
funding is available, it's just not being used.''
   Among those at the Thursday meeting were Attorney General Edwin
Meese III, Education Secretary William Bennett and Transportation
Secretary Jim Burnley.
</TEXT>
