<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gonzalez-Spain     04-30 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gonzalez-Spain,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain's Prime Minister Urges More Respect for His `Awakening'
Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Spanish prime minister has a message
for Americans who think Spain is a sleepy, dusty country crippled
by years of dictatorship.
   Felipe Gonzalez, who was elected in 1982, is in the United
States making what amounts to an announcement that his country
should no longer be considered the Rodney Dangerfield of Europe.
Spain wants some respect.
   ``We'd like to change the nature of relations between the United
States and Spain,'' Gonzalez said Friday, speaking through an
interpreter in his hotel room. ``Above all, we want Spain to be
accepted by the United States as we are now. Spain is going to be
economically sound by the end of the century.''
   The year 1992, Gonzalez said, marks Spain's ``awakening'' from
Francisco Franco's 36-year rule that ended with Franco's death in
1975.
   In four years, the Summer Olympics will be held in Barcelona, a
World's Fair will take place in Seville and the 500th anniversary
of Christopher Columbus' voyage will be celebrated in Madrid.
   The year 1992 also marks the completion of Spain's integration
into the European Economic Community.
   ``Over the last 10 years that have gone by, the economy has
begun producing rapidly,'' said Gonzalez. ``Spain for over half a
century had a hyper-protectionist economy but now that it's opened
up we've seen rapid development and economic growth. This is what
we want to communicate to the U.S.''
   On Thursday, speaking at Harvard University, Gonzalez said Spain
was part of a growing political and economic union in Western
Europe that could lead to a stronger NATO alliance.
   However, the 46-year-old prime minister said it will take time
for Spain to recover from Franco's regime. At present, the per
capita income in Spain is less than half of West Germany's, he said.
</TEXT>
