<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TuskegeeProtest     04-30 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tuskegee Protest,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Temporary Restraining Order Against University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSKEGEE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday allowed Tuskegee University
to bar students who owe more than $300 in overdue fees from taking
final exams, a school spokesman said.
   Judge Howard F. Bryan of Macon County dissolved the restraining
order he had issued Wednesday against enforcement of the policy,
said J.J. Johnson.
   Students who owe more than $300 on Monday _ when final exams
begin _ will not be allowed to take their tests, Johnson said.
   University officials testified Friday that 600 students owed
more than $300 in fees, said Michael Pintard, president of the
Student Government Association. The judge ordered Tuskegee to open
its business office all day Saturday and part of Sunday so students
could make payments on overdue fees, Johnson said.
   The university announced earlier that abuse of an installment
plan had prompted it to enforce its policy barring students with
overdue fees from attending class or taking exams. Officials
estimated 2,000 students owe almost $1.5 million.
   The crackdown had sparked a week of protests, including a sit-in
at the administration building last weekend.
   Student leaders said the university should have warned students
earlier about the crackdown and should have allowed students in
financial difficulty to work out a timetable for repayment.
   Pintard calling the judge's ruling Friday a ``serious
miscarriage of justice.''
   University President Benjamin Payton said the ruling
``underscores the fact that when students make loans they have to
pay them.''
   ``What everybody needs to be clear about, however, is this is
not a case of Tuskegee University fighting its students,'' Payton
said. ``It's a case of Tuskegee University insisting that students
learn very important lessons for life.''
</TEXT>
