<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0878,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Close At Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with closing figures. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed at a
record high Saturday for the second consecutive trading day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
242.15 points Thursday, added another 75.42 points, or 0.16
percent, to finish Saturday's half-day session at 27,509.54.
   ``The Tokyo market has been in good, stable condition without
any bad news to prompt selling,'' said a stock analyst for a major
brokerage, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Japanese yen's stability on foreign exchange markets also
has helped boost stock prices, he said.
   Trading was a relatively quiet 450 million shares on the
market's first section Saturday because of the holiday-studded
``Golden Week'' which started Friday, traders said. During
Thursday's full-day session, 800 million shares were traded.
   Popular issues included electricals, machineries and chemicals.
Foodstuffs, textiles and real estates also gained ground, while
some drugs and banks declined.
   Most major Japanese financial institutions will be closed
Wednesday through Friday because of holidays.
   The Tokyo foreign exchange market normally is closed on
Saturdays.
</TEXT>
