<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CondorEgg 3rdLd-Writethru a0892 04-30 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condor Egg, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0892,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Condor Chick Hatches With Help From Its Keepers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs to UPDATE with comments from news conference.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, `A recording...' Edits to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first California condor conceived in
captivity hatched Friday, its keepers using tweezers and their
fingertips to help the newest member of the nearly extinct species
break free from its shell, officials said.
   ``It's alive and it looks healthy,'' said Tom Hanscom, a
spokesman for the San Diego Wild Animal Park. ``It's resting now.
We don't have any other details.''
   The hatching represents a tremendous boost to efforts to save
the species. It brings the known population of North America's
largest land bird to 28, all in captivity _ 15 at the park here and
13 at the Los Angeles Zoo.
   The squawking infant, named Molloko, an Indian word for
``condor,'' was swaddled in a towel and placed in the same type of
incubator used for premature infants.
   ``Early this morning there were 27 California condors left in
the world,'' said Bill Toone, curator of birds at the park. ``This
afternoon there's 28 of them, and we couldn't be more excited about
that.
   ``When the numbers are so low, one bird is seen as a very big
step away from extinction,'' Toone added.
   Although the tiny bird was not brought forth to ``meet the
press,'' its history-making birth was recorded on videotape and
shown at a press conference Friday night.
   Earlier, the chick had become stuck in dried membrane and
albumen and could no longer rotate in the shell to peck its way
out. Its keepers removed it cautiously because of the danger of
rupturing blood vessels linked to egg membranes.
   A recording of vultures making hissing and grunting sounds was
played at intervals to duplicate the sounds the chick would hear in
a natural setting.
   Park officials had said they intended to intervene by Saturday
if the chick, which began hatching Wednesday, hadn't emerged from
the shell. Allowing the hatching struggle to continue would
overexhaust the bird.
   The chick, conceived by the only known activing breeding pair of
the California condor, was expected to weigh about 9 ounces,
Hanscom said. The species has a wingspan of up to 10 feet at
maturity.
   The 10-ounce blue-green egg, about 5 inches long, had been under
a 24-hour watch since Wednesday, when keepers noticed ``pip''
cracks in one end signaling the start of hatching, which can take
three days.
   After the egg was laid March 3, it was taken away from the
parent birds and incubated artificially in hopes that the female
bird would produce a second egg. So far, this has not happened.
   It will be a while before the sex of the bird can be determined
through a blood test, officials said.
   Hanscom said that representatives of the Chumash Indian tribe
had been enlisted to select the name for the chick upon hatching.
   The tribe inhabited the Santa Barbara area that most recently
served as California condor habitat, and the bird figures
prominently in the tribe's religion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880430-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Stark     04-30 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Stark,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producer Ray Stark Gives Siskel and Ebert Two Thumbs Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producer Ray Stark, stung by negative reviews
of ``Biloxi Blues'' from televison movie critics Gene Siskel and
Roger Ebert, has sent the two a letter calling them a ``critical
version of Laurel and Hardy.''
   ``Your thumb system is a clever bit of show business; I suggest
you sit on them,'' Stark said, referring to the pair's trademark
``thumbs up'' or ``thumbs down'' method of evaluation.
   Siskel responded that someone perhaps had purloined Stark's
stationery to write a rude note.
   Stark, calling the two a ``critical version of Laurel and
Hardy,'' said he will suggest to fellow producers that they refrain
from offering early screenings to the pair.
   ``Biloxi Blues,'' about an Army recruit from Brooklyn who gets
his basic training in the Deep South, is based on a play by Neil
Simon, stars Matthew Broderick and was directed by Mike Nichols.
Stark is the head of Rastar Productions, which produced the film.
   In an April 20 letter to Siskel at the Chicago Tribune, Stark
recounts several positive reviews of ``Biloxi Blues'' that appeared
in the New York Times, Time magazine, the Washington Post, Los
Angeles Times, and the Chicago Tribune.
   But ``there on television was Roger Ebert saying `I realized to
my shock that his (Nichols) career has gone nowhere in recent
years. ... What has happened to him as a director? ... He's just
another one of the hacks brought in to direct another Neil Simon
screenplay.'
   ``And there were you agreeing, `I think the word hack is right.
... I was very shocked at how dull the film was,''' Stark wrote to
Siskel.
   ``For such men of the world, the two of you shock very easily,''
said Stark in the three-page letter, listing a number of problems
such as Middle East tensions, AIDS, and homelessness.
   The letter was sent to the heads of several major studios.
   In a letter obtained by the Washington Post, Siskel replied to
Stark and referred to an earlier, apparently friendlier, letter.
   ``I think you should know that someone using your name and good
stationery has just violated the reasonable opinions of the earlier
letter you sent me,'' Siskel wrote. ``I suggest that you have
someone stand guard at your desk to make sure that no crackpot gets
ahold of your letterhead.''
</TEXT>
