<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Strike-Scene     04-30 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Strike-Scene,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Determined To Win Higher Pay From Government They Don't
Trust</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers glared with icy determination at
platoons of plainclothes police as they streamed out through the
gates of the huge strike-bound Lenin steelworks during a shift
change.
   Striding toward a bus stop, a few flashed the V-for-victory sign
once out of sight of police. Their strike at the plant in the
Krakow suburb of Nowa Huta has shaken the government at the highest
level.
   At the bus stop 100 yards from the gates, a knot of workers
began to talk freely with foreign reporters.
   ``They have to give people what they deserve,'' A beefy man in a
shiny tan jacket said of communist authorities.
   He punched the air angrily with his finger as he spoke: ``We are
working. Prices are going up. We have no money.''
   Others murmured agreement and nodded.
   It was Friday night and workers had occuped the plant for four
days, demanding pay raises, the restoration of union rights and
reinstatement of dismissed Solidarity activists.
   A worker on the edge of the group said he made $107 a month,
half of which he must spend on the maintenance and mortgage on his
home: ``We are working all the time, on Sundays too. And we can
hardly live.''
   Prices have gone up 42 percent so far this year as the result of
government reforms aimed at making the economy more market-oriented.
   ``We don't believe them anymore,'' a middle-aged man with a
quiet manner said of authorities. ``They keep promising (that
things will get better) and yet we can't earn in one day even
enough for two kilos (4 pounds) of herring.
   ``They share millions and we are near starvation.''
   The workers have been inside the plant for 16 hours at a stretch
during the strike, the nation's worst since martial law stifled the
Solidarity independent labor federation 6{ yearss ago. Strikers
spend their day at the plant sitting, talking, tinkering, but not
working.
   They said some workers have not joined the stoppage and toil
while their colleagues in a neighboring department sit idle.
   The strike committee says it represents half the plant's 32,000
workers, and from 12,000 to 14,000 workers are in the plant at any
one time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880430-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ForestFireSpring Bjt   04-30 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fire Spring, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spring Brings Blooms To Charred Ruins Of Forest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As spring returns to this rugged
country, plants, bushes and trees that have evolved to live with
fire are sprouting among ruined woodlands charred by Oregon's worst
forest fire in 50 years.
   One of the patches of color dotting the shiny blacks and dull
browns of burned trees in the Kalmiopsis Wilderness is the pink
flower of the Kalmiopsis bush, which needs periodic fires to
survive.
   ``It lives in some pretty rough places,'' said Lee Webb, a
wildlife biologist for the Siskiyou National Forest. ``Maybe what
happens is it lives where the fire doesn't hit. You expect fire to
burn places it's been before.
   ``It grows in the harshest sites because it can't compete. As
things go on and sites become better, it loses ground to other
plants. When the fire comes through and it is growing in these
little sanctuaries, it has a competitive edge.''
   He and Tom Atzet, a U.S. Forest Service regional ecologist,
scrambled down a steep slope of crumbling rock recently to a dead
canyon of live oak marked with white flags. The clump of Kalmiopsis
that survived was sheltered by the seared leaves of the oak trees.
   In other parts of the wilderness, the forest is healing itself
as loggers and environmentalists fight over whether to salvage the
96,500 acres of burned timber and replant the land or leave the job
to Mother Nature.
   Atzet stopped to dig out a fawn lilly, also known as a trout
lilly, blooming where just months before fire seared the soil's
surface.
   ``The lillies are just loving it,'' Atzet said. ``They store all
their energy underground in this bulb. Whether there is a fire or
not during the summer, it doesn't care.
   ``We are finding that leachates from the ash left by the fire
stimulate these things to grow. That gives them a competitive
advantage (against plants knocked back by the fire). It's a war out
here for every bit of nitrogen and every bit of water.''
   Madrone and sugar pine on one slope had been killed by a
fast-moving wall of flame that roared down Silver Creek. But now
many of the plants show tiny green sprouts around the bases of
their trunks.
   Throughout the North Kalmiopsis Roadless Area of the Siskiyou
National Forest, these evergreen hardwoods valued as clean-burning
firewood are grouped in rings, evidence that fire has been a
frequent visitor. Each time the sprouts return after a fire, the
ring grows wider.
   Where the fire overran the remains of a cleared area near
Chinaman Hat, new Douglas fir seedlings already have been planted
for a new forest.
   Atzet stopped again to drill into the bulging ``cat face'' of a
sugar pine. The cat face is a ring of bulging bark that has grown
to heal a scar left by a previous fire. Because the healing bark is
loaded with pitch, it tends to burn more intensely each time fire
sweeps past, and the cat face grows.
   ``I've found trees here that are 200 years old that have burned
four or five times,'' Atzet said.
   By examining the older trees, Atzet has found that fire returns
to the Kalmiopsis an average of every 50 years.
   ``It could be 150 years or it could be 25, but the average is
50,'' said Atzet. ``If we look at our records, we find that there
was a fire in the Kalmiopsis area in the 1930s, so this one was
right on schedule.''
   He bored into a sugar pine that was blackened around the base
but retained a green canopy. He pulled out a core of damp wood and
examined the largely undamaged cambium layer beneath the bark,
which allows a tree to form new bark and wood.
   ``What fire?'' he exclaimed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
