<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   04-30 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Warns Against Complacency, Jackson Plans Anti-Dukakis Ads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: May be topped.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis is telling Ohio
supporters not to be lulled by polls giving him a safe lead, while
party rival Jesse Jackson is stepping up his criticism of the
Massachusetts governor.
   Vice President George Bush, meanwhile, told supporters on Friday
that he's ready to let Democrats have a taste of some of their own
medicine if they try to raise the ``sleaze factor'' against him.
   Bush, the certain Republican nominee, also challenged the two
Democrats to join him in supporting the death penalty for ``drug
kingpins.''
   Dukakis was campaigning today in Cincinnati and Cleveland before
traveling to next-door Indiana, where he planned events in
Indianapolis. Dukakis is expecting to add to his string of
victories when both states hold their primaries Tuesday.
   Jackson's attempt to chip away at the Dukakis lead will
intensify Sunday and Monday when he will air TV ads saying ``Mike
Dukakis wants to manage the damage'' left from the Reagan
administration, campaign manager Gerald Austin said. The ads say
Jackson ``wants to change the course of America.''
   Austin, who managed Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste's 1982 and 1986
campaigns, said Jackson is spending $400,000 on media in the battle
for Ohio's 159 delegates to the Democratic National Convention this
summer
   Jackson on Friday assailed Dukakis for not wanting to classify
South Africa as a terrorist state for allegedly supporting rebels
battling Mozambique. Dukakis has rejected Jackson's call to provide
arms to Mozambique's Marxist government to fight the rebels.
   Celeste appeared with Dukakis before a union audience in
Columbus but did not endorse him. Celeste planned to appear with
Jackson in Cleveland on Sunday.
   Celeste said he wanted ``to ensure an open, enthusiastic primary
in the state.''
   Dukakis told crowds across the state, ``I hope you won't pay
attention to these polls.'' He recalled his 1978 race for
re-election as governor of Massachusetts when he lost despite a
huge lead, as much as 50 points at one point in the polls.
   Polls in Ohio are giving Dukakis a 2-to-1 lead over Jackson.
With more than 1,250 delegates in the Associated Press total,
Dukakis enjoys a lead of roughly 400 over Jackson. He is also
beginning to win over committed delegates from the suspended
campaigns of Tennessee Sen. Al Gore and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon.
   Dukakis is trying to make a major issue in industrial Ohio of
President Reagan's vow to veto the trade bill passed by the Senate
because of the provision requiring companies to give 60 days notice
before closing plants. He said a similar law in Massachusetts had
``cushioned the blow'' and ``helped us to save thousands of jobs
and hundreds of companies.''
   Massachusetts state officials say, however, the plant closing
law has not ``saved'' workers' jobs but has helped some 24,000 find
new employment after plant closings.
   Bush was campaigning today in Ohio, including stops in Cleveland
and at an Ohio State University spring football scrimmage.
   Bush said Friday in interviews in Indianapolis he is not worried
about his campaign being hurt by current investigations into
Attorney General Edwin Meese III and Meese's business associates.
   He also said he did not think the ``sleaze'' issue hurts him.
   ``I think the Democrats are trying to make it that, but we will
have some fun, too, trying to look into what is going on in
Illinois or Massachusetts depending upon which one wins the
Democratic nomination,'' he said.
   At a rally in Indianapolis, Bush said: ``Let me throw this
challenge down. I favor the death penalty for narcotics kingpins.
Now will the Democrats join us on that or not?''
</TEXT>
