<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     04-30 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Urges Ohio Supporers Not To Take Victory For Granted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is insisting ``it's not
all over'' and urging Ohio supporters to ignore polls and other
signs that he is advancing strongly toward the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   Dukakis, expecting to add to his string of victories in Ohio and
Indiana primaries on Tuesday, all but ignored his remaining party
rival Jesse Jackson while campaigning across Ohio on Friday.
Instead, he focused on criticizing the Reagan administration on
trade legislation and other issues.
   He was campaigning today in Cincinnati and Cleveland before
traveling to next-door Indiana, where he planned events in
Indianapolis.
   At every stop as he criss-crossed Ohio, Dukakis told crowds, ``I
hope you won't pay attention to these polls.'' He recalled his 1978
race for re-election as governor of Massachusetts when he lost
despite a huge lead, as much as 50 points at one point in the polls.
   ``What I am concerned about,'' Dukakis said, ``... is people
looking at polls and taking them seriously and assuming that it's
all over.
   ``It's not all over, and I know that better than anybody from
rather painful personal experience.''
   Dukakis, who holds a commanding lead in the delegate race and is
the undisputed front-runner, has come under sharpened criticism
from Jackson over the past two days.
   Dukakis turned aside questions about his rival's charge that he
would only ``manage'' President Reagan's ecomomic program, not
change it.
   ``I just don't talk about those things,'' Dukakis said. ``I have
a record. The White House would be very much surprised if they
learned all of a sudden Michael Dukakis was going to manage
Reaganomics _ they don't believe that for one minute.''
   The Massachusetts governor is seeking to make a major issue in
industrial Ohio of the president's vow to veto the trade bill
passed by the Senate because of the provision requiring companies
to give 60 days notice before closing plants. He said a similar law
in Massachusetts had ``cushioned the blow'' and ``helped us to save
thousands of jobs and hundreds of companies.''
   However, because the Massachusetts law requests _ but does not
require _ companies to provide workers with 90 days warning before
a plant closing, Dukakis administration officials in Boston have
been unable to offer evidence the notification provision has
accomplished its goal.
   Massachusetts state officials say the plant closing law has not
``saved'' workers' jobs but has helped some 24,000 find new
employment after plant closings.
   Ohio's Democratic Gov. Richard Celeste appeared with Dukakis
before a union audience in Columbus, but did not endorse him and
planned to appear with Jackson in Cleveland on Sunday.
   Celeste said he wanted ``to ensure an open, enthusiastic primary
in the state, in which Rev. Jackson knows he's as welcome as Gov.
Dukakis at every place, including the governor's office, and his
supporters know we expect them to be part of a unified effort in
the fall.''
   Despite his insistence the race is not over, Dukakis struck an
optimistic note as he urged a lunchtime crowd in Dayton to help
bring a large voter turnout. ``If we do, we're going to win in
Ohio, we're going to win in Indiana, we're going to win in West
Virginia and in California and in New Jersey, and win this
nomination,'' he said.
</TEXT>
