<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua     04-30 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Drop Demand; 11 Arrested In Demonstrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel leaders dropped a demand that
their fighters receive ammunition and weapons after moving into
cease-fire zones, removing a major obstacle in peace talks with the
government.
   Also Friday, the leftist Sandinista government's labor troubles
persisted and police used rubber truncheons to quell protests by
striking auto mechanics and construction workers, arresting 11
demonstrators.
   The decision by leaders of the rebels, known as Contras, not to
demand arms supplies after their fighters move into the seven
cease-fire zones removed a key barrier to achieving a lasting peace
under accords signed March 23.
   ``We have desisted from receiving replacements of weapons and
ammunition in the zones and we accept the concept of sovereignty
and indivisibility of national territory,'' top Contra leader
Adolfo Calero told a news conference.
   The Contras had also insisted that the cease-fire zones be
autonomous.
   Calero said, however, that the Contras rejected the government's
demand that more than $17 million in humanitarian aid to the
rebels, recently approved by the U.S. Congress, be channeled
through the International Red Cross.
   The aid was to be funneled to Nicaragua through the U.S. Agency
for International Development.
   Under the March 23 agreement signed in the southern border town
of Sapoa, only neutral parties may distribute the aid.
   The rebels have been supported by Washington since 1981, when
they mounted the insurgency that has claimed more than 26,000
lives. The Sapoa accords promise them a role in the political
process in a more democratic Nicaragua.
   Earlier Friday, the rebels turned down a government proposal to
extend by a month a 60-day cease-fire that began April 1. They said
the Sandinista offer showed ``a lack of good will to fulfill the
agreements.''
   In Washington, President Reagan said Friday he would continue to
apply economic sanctions against Nicaragua to counter the ``unusual
and extraordinary threat to the national security and foreign
policy of the United States'' posed by the Sandinista regime.
   In a semi-annual report required by law, Reagan said trade
sanctions ``complement the diplomatic and other aspects of our
policy toward Nicaragua.''
   One of the two labor protests in Managua on Friday came outside
the General Workers Confederation, an umbrella group for
anti-Sandinista unions, where 38 construction workers and auto
mechanics went on a hunger strike Sunday.
   On Friday night, about 80 university students staged a march in
sympathy with about 1,500 workers from both industries who have
been on strike for higher wages since Feb. 25.
   The students passed near the union headquarters, chanting ``A
Free Fatherland!.'' Riot squads standing by did not interfere, but
the police cordoned off the building's entrance.
   A banner strung across the building said: ``We prefer to die of
hunger fighting with dignity than to die working as slaves.''
   Meanwhile, Jose Castillo Osejo, an opposition leader and
director of privately-owned Radio Corporation, claimed Interior
Minister Tomas Borge summoned him to his office, berated the radio
for its reporting of the demonstrations and punched him in the
mouth.
   Castillo, a leader of a private human rights group and the
opposition Conservative Party, said Borge later apologized.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
