<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Angola     04-30 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Angola,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting on Southern Africa Set Next Week In London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of South Africa and Angola will meet
for the first time to discuss a peace settlement that will include
the possible withdrawal of Cuban forces from Angola when they join
delegates from the United States and Cuba in London next week.
   The delegations also will confer on other regional issues,
including the status of a parallel effort to bring about
independence and black majority rule in Namibia or Southwest
Africa, which is under South African administration, the State
Department said Friday.
   The American delegation to the May 3-4 talks will be headed by
Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker, State Department
spokesman Charles Redman said. Cuban officials will join the talks
as part of the Angolan delegation.
   South African and Angolan forces have been intermittently
involved militarily since the Marxist government assumed power in
Maputo in 1975.
   South Africa sent troops into Angola last summer in support of
UNITA, Angola's U.S.-backed rebel movement. South African officials
have said the number of troops has been sharply reduced from a peak
of 3,000.
   The United States has given high priority to reaching an
agreement that would lead to the withdrawal of the estimated 40,000
Cuban troops in Angola, a close ally of the Soviet Union.
   U.S. officials were encouraged last January when Angola and Cuba
agreed for the first time to the principle of a total Cuban
withdrawal from Angola. There has been no agreement, however, on a
timetable.
   Angola's main interests are an end to American assistance to the
rebel movement in Angola and to the withdrawal of South African
forces in Angola.
   A delegation from the Organization of African Unity met with
Crocker two weeks ago and said the United States should end all aid
to the Angolan rebels as a means of helping the peace process but
officials said Crocker turned down the request.
</TEXT>
