<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     04-30 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Tries To Show Dukakis As Weak On Foreign, Domestic Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says he intends to ``raise the
level'' of the campaign debate as he takes on Democratic
presidential rival Michael Dukakis over fiscal and foreign policy.
   In an uphill bid to close in on Dukakis' widening delegate lead,
Jackson is painting the Massachusetts governor as a candidate who
has not shown a strong willingness to undo President Reagan's
legacy.
   Campaigning under Cleveland's cold rainy skies for votes in
Tuesday's Ohio primary, Jackson hit Dukakis on two issues _
southern Africa and Reaganomics.
   He said Dukakis lacks understanding about southern Africa,
particlarly in Mozambique where Jackson said Dukakis is to the
right of President Reagan.
   Jackson also vowed Friday to intensify his quest for the
nomination after a string of primary losses to Dukakis.
   He told a labor rally in Cleveland: ``I'm not behind. I'm so far
in front of where I started. We've come too far from where we
started and I don't feel no way tired. We're going all the way.''
   It was clear Jackson's strategy is to paint sharp distinctions
between himself and Dukakis, criticizing his rival as lacking in
clear policy positions.
   He said Dukakis would not give military aid to Mozambique in the
face of South-Africa backed rebel brutality against civilians. That
is someting even Reagan favors, Jackson said.
   Jackson told reporters traveling on his campaign bus that
Dukakis does not understand the policy options in Africa, but that
he was not questioning the governor's motivation.
   ``His intention I'm convinced would be to end apartheid,''
Jackson said. ``But we need a plan and a commitment to end
apartheid ... It is clear when he takes a position to the right of
Reagan that is bad judgment ... He does not understand the options
in southern Africa.
   ``It's my intention to raise the general level of the foreign
policy debate.''
   Also on Friday, Jackson campaign manager Gerald Austin said the
campaign will unveil a new television commercial Sunday and Monday.
   He said the campaign will spend $400,000 on media in Ohio.
   The ad, consisting of a series of still shots, will have a
voice-over saying that Vice President George Bush wants to stay the
course, ``Mike Dukakis wants to manage the damage'' and ``Jackson
wants to change the course of America.''
