<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     04-30 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Democrats Choose Controversial Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a rowdy and contentious
convention, the governing Christian Democratic Party chose wealthy
businessman Julio Adolfo Rey Prendes as its candidate in next
year's presidential elections.
   The choice Friday set off a controversy that could split the
party.
   Rey Prendes, a former Cabinet minister, was chosen by
acclamation as the sole entry in the convention marked by insults,
boos, whistles and catcalls.
   Fidel Chavez Mena, his bitter rival and a former foreign
minister, boycotted the convention and so did President Jose
Napoleon Duarte.
   The president, the party's honorary chairman, had urged both
contenders to step aside in favor of a ``unity candidate.''
   The two rivals, as well as the convention, ignored a dramatic
appeal earlier in the week to put aside their differences and back
Abraham Gonzalez, a party veteran, in order to maintain unity
within the centrist organization.
   Duarte warned that a rift in Christian Democratic ranks will
weaken the party and leave the field wide open to its chief rival,
the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, which has already won
control of the National Legislature and a majority of mayorships in
mid-term elections March 20.
   By law, Duarte could not run for a second five-year term. He won
the presidency in the midst of a leftist civil war against the
U.S.-supported conservative government that began in 1980 and
continues.
   Months ago, Rey Prendes wrested control of the party machinery
from the Duarte and Chavez Mena factions, so Chavez Mena was at big
disadvantage throughout the race.
   Aquilino Duarte, a nephew of the president and member of the
party's 10-member directorate, predicted the choice ``is going to
shatter'' the party.
   Also addressing the delegates before the acclamation vote,
Roberto Vieira, another directorate member, warned amid boos: ``If
we make this decision and the party splits, the people will not
have a democratic option in the presidential election.''
   Rey Prendes expressed hope there will be no split.
   ``I'm sure that once tempers cool, we'll all be together again
in the struggle. Let the anger end today,'' he said in an
acceptance speech.
   ``My arms are open. There is no need to exclude anyone,'' he
said in what was taken as a reference to Chavez Mena.
   Rey Prendes is a former presidential press spokesman, a
Cabinet-level job, a former mayor of San Salvador and a member of
the directorate. He and Chavez Mena helped found the party in 1960.
</TEXT>
