<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Durenberger-EthicsLetter     04-30 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Durenberger-Ethics Letter,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Durenberger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the letter from the Senate
Select Committee on Ethics to Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., on
its investigation of his public comments on intelligence matters:
   Dear Senator Durenberger:
   The Select Committee has received and investigated allegations
that certain of your public statements violated Senate Resolution
400.
   Senate Resolution 400 prohibits the disclosure of classified
intelligence information which has been provided to the Select
Committee on Intelligence, and imposes a duty upon each senator to
exercise special care when discussing intelligence matters. As the
immediate former chairman of the Intelligence Committee you are
under a particular and substantial obligation to comply with the
letter and spirit of Senate Resolution 400.
   The Ethics Committee has determined that your statements gave
the appearance that you were disclosing sensitive national security
information and such appearance jeopardized the mutual confidence
which must exist between the Congress and the intelligence
community.
   Because the committee has concluded that your actions were not
intentional, deliberate, nor attended with gross negligence, and
because of the particular facts of this case, we will not recommend
that the Senate take institutional action against you. However, the
committee wants to make it clear that it does not condone your
actions.''
   (Signed) Sen. Howell Heflin, chairman, Sen. Warren B. Rudman,
vice chairman, and Sens. David Pryor, Terry Sanford, Jesse Helms
and Nancy Kassebaum.
</TEXT>
