<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Handguns     04-30 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Handguns,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Asked To Decide on Lawsuits Against Makers of Cheap Handguns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has asked for the view
of a District of Columbia court on whether makers of handguns like
the one used to shoot President Reagan can be sued for deaths and
injuries when those guns are used.
   The legal issue was referred Friday to the District of Columbia
Court of Appeals in a case involving Thomas K. Delahanty, a former
District of Columbia policeman, one of three people wounded by
presidential assailant John W. Hinckley Jr. in the 1981 shooting.
Delahanty had tried to sue the gun manufacturer.
   The action by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington
raises the possibility that Delahanty and former White House press
Secretary James Brady may revive lawsuits against Roehm
Gesellschaft, the West German manufacturer of the .22-caliber
pistol used by Hinckley.
   The federal court sought the D.C. court's view because federal
courts must apply the laws of the states in which they are located
to civil suits.
   The court noted that Maryland law should be consulted since the
District of Columbia was carved out of Maryland when the nation's
capital was formed.
   A 1985 ruling by Maryland's highest court made gun makers and
sellers liable for injuries and death caused by the criminal use of
so-called Saturday Night Specials.
   The federal court's requst _ an advisory opinion _ is merely a
suggestion and does not require a ruling by the D.C. court.
   Richard Gardiner, assistant general counsel of the National
Rifle Association, said of Friday's advisory opinion, ``It's
obviously disappointing that this court didn't simply say this
theory is so outlandish that we're not going to pay any attention
to it.''
   The advisory opinion came a year after the same appellate court
upheld the dismissal of Brady's suit against Roehm and its U.S.
subsidiary, R.G. Industries.
   In that ruling, the court held Brady did not raise a valid
negligence claim because gun manufacturers were not obligated ``to
prevent criminals from using their products.''
</TEXT>
