<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Defeats Bid To Make States Ante Up for Super Collider</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee says states seeking the
super collider atom smasher will not have to put up at least $500
million in cash or services to land the eagerly pursued research
installation.
   The Space, Science and Technology Committee on Friday, in a
20-11 vote, rejected the minimum-funds amendment offered by Rep.
Ron Packard, R-Calif., for the $4.4 billion superconducting super
collider.
   Committee members also voted 16-14 against an alternative that
would have required the secretary of energy to report to the
committee in six months his recommendations for what the winning
state should pay.
   The amendments were offered to the $3.1 billion Energy
Department research authorization bill.
   As it stands, the bill would authorize $1.6 billion over the
next three years for the collider, of which $148 million would be
for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 _ but with no construction
funds until Oct. 1, 1989.
   Several amendments to the bill remain to be considered,
including measures that would sharply reduce the super collider
authorization or eliminate it altogether, and to make a 25 percent
foreign contribution a requirement for proceeding with the giant
atom smasher.
</TEXT>
