<HEAD>Counter-Terrorism Official Predicts Rise in Palestinian Terror</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top U.S. counter-terrorism expert says there
is likely to be a surge in Palestinian terrorism as a result of the
uprising in the Israeli-occupied territories and the killing of a
Palestinian guerrilla chieftain.
   Ambassador L. Paul Bremer said Friday that Libya continues to
plan international terrorist attacks, but is looking for such
surrogates as the Japanese Red Army ``to do its dirty work.''
   In an interview, Bremer said, ``There is a possibility of a
measurable increase of Palestinian terrorism'' in the coming months
because of the five-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip and the killing of
Khalil Wazir, the second-in-command of the Palestine Liberation
Organization by Israeli agents.
   The rapprochement between PLO chief Yasser Arafat and Syrian
President Hafez Assad following the assassination of Wazir, also
known as Abu Jihad, may contribute to a terror campaign, although
it is too soon to assess the impact of the thaw, he said.
   The rapprochement between PLO chief Yasser Arafat and Syrian
President Hafez Assad following Abu Jihad's assassination also may
contribute to a terror campaign, although it is too soon to assess
the impact of the thaw, he said.
   Bremer also said that Abu Nidal, who heads a Palestinian faction
which broke away from the Arafat's Fatah branch of the PLO
continues to plan terror attacks from his headquarters in Libya
where he maintains 300 to 400 operatives.
