<HEAD>More Than 1,000 Mariel Cuban Detainees Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says more than 1,000
Mariel Cuban detainess have been released into halfway houses or
family sponsors in communities since prison disturbances conducted
by them last fall.
   Delays in placing the detainees in halfway houses was one of the
issues n as triggering last year's uprisings at federal prisons in
Atlanta and Oakdale, La. Federal officials had said they were
having trouble finding space in the halfway houses for the
detainees.
   From last June until the time the prison riots erupted in
November, the Immigration and Naturalization Service had released
only 106 Cuban inmates to halfway houses or to family sponsors. A
total of 1,047 have been placed since the disturbances.
   INS has approved 2,224 Cuban detainees for release since last
June, of whom 1,337 have been approved since the riots.
   Parole has been denied to 1,193 Mariel Cubans and 845 of the
denials have been decided since the uprisings.
