<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EEC-Turkey     04-30 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EEC-Turkey,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Year After Applying, Turkey EEC Membership Still Doubtful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MILAN RUZICKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a year after Turkey asked to
join the European Economic Community, its membership prospects are
distant, frustrated by its rivalry with Greece.
   Talks collapsed this week after a Greek-inspired quarrel over
the presence of 29,000 Turkish troops in Cyprus.
   Relations between Greece and Turkey, two NATO allies that almost
went to war last year over rights to explore for minerals in the
Aegean Sea, are so poor that one diplomat of the Western alliance
told a reporter at its Brussels headquarters: ``Don't ask me about
Greece and Turkey in this building.''
   On Monday, a meeting in Luxembourg of EEC and Turkish officials
was canceled at the last minute following the fight inspired by
Greece, an EEC member since 1981.
   The bid to revive ties with Turkey ended in ``vituperative
exchanges'' between Greek and Turkish officials at dinner, one
source said.
   A session afterwards with foreign ministers was abruptly
canceled.
   ``I don't think any one of us expected this to happen,'' said
Foreign Minister Jacques Poos of Luxembourg.
   ``It was not a failure,'' said Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher of West Germany. The meeting simply ``did not take place.''
   Mesud Yilmaz, the Turkish foreign minister, refused to accept
the EEC view, contained in a statement, that the presence of
Turkish troops in northern Cyprus ``affects the relations'' between
it and Turkey.
   Yilmaz said the Turkish troops on Cyprus are none of the EEC's
business. Turkey invaded Cyprus in 1974 to protect the Turkish
Cypriot minority after a pro-Athens coup there.
   But Cyprus, like Turkey, has an association accord with the EEC
and also aspires to join the Common Market someday. The accord
gives Turkey trade privileges, development aid and a forum to
discuss EEC membership.
   The accord was suspended after a 1980 military coup in Turkey,
freezing an $748 million aid deal.
   The cancellation of Monday's meeting was embarrassing for West
Germany, Turkey's staunchest EEC ally.
   It has had good relations with Turkey for more than 100 years.
In the 1930s, many thousands of Germans fled their country's Nazi
regime to find exile in Turkey.
   The collapse of the EEC-Turkey talks was all the more surprising
as it followed recent meetings between Andreas Papandreou and
Turgut Ozal, the Greek and Turkish prime ministers, who agreed to
step up cooperation.
   It was hoped a new meeting on the issue can be held before June
30. On that day, West Germany hands over the EEC's rotating
presidency to Greece for six months dimming hopes for progress even
further.
   Turkey is eager to join the EEC. It prides itself in having a
rapid economic growth and liberal economic policies and sees itself
as a bridge between Europe and the volatile Middle East.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880430-0043 </DOCNO>
