<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JetBlast-Passengers     04-30 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Blast-Passengers,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frightened Passengers Of Stricken Jet Praise Pilot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jet Blast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAHULUI, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight attendant was serving drinks to
a passenger and as ``their hands just touched'' she disappeared in
an explosion that ripped open the jetliner 24,000 feet above the
Pacific Ocean, a passenger said.
   Coast Guard searchers Friday failed to find any trace of
Clarabelle Lansing, 57, who had worked 37 years for Aloha Airlines.
   ``She was just handing my wife a drink,'' William Flanigan said.
``She had stopped and told us this was the last call. We were going
to be descending.
   ``And then, whoosh! She was gone. Their hands just touched when
it happened.''
   Sixty-one people were injured Thursday in the accident aboard
Flight 243. Federal investigators said they were focusing on
possible structural failure in the 19-year-old plane.
   Passengers praised Capt. Robert Schornstheimer, 42, who flew the
badly crippled plane for about 15 minutes before making an
emergency landing on Maui. After leaving the plane, many of those
who were uninjured sought out the pilot and shook his hand.
   ``It's tremendous how he controlled the plane,'' passenger
Ignazio Marinello said. ``The wind was so fantastic; without him
we'd never be alive.''
   ``I'm so amazed the pilot of the airplane did land it,'' said
James Toyooka, who said his three days of research for a stock
brokerage company went flying out the plane.
   ``I couldn't believe it _ that people are still alive,'' he said.
   Passengers said that even though the plane was rocking as it
headed toward the Maui airport, the landing was smooth.
   ``It was just like riding in a Cadillac,'' said John Lopez of
Hilo.
   The pilot's father, also named Robert Schornstheimer, said in an
interview from his Marietta, Ohio, home that his son didn't seem
unsettled when he spoke with him by telephone Thursday night after
the accident.
   ``When we talked to him he was still feeling pretty calm,'' he
said. ``He said you're calm about it when you're doing it, but
afterwards you start thinking about it.''
   ``He says it was just something else _ all of a sudden there was
this noise, and the plane's flying funny and there's a big drag on
it, so he immediately decided to change the flight plan to land at
the Maui airport, which was closest, and he was able to get it in
and land it,'' Schornstheimer said.
   In spite of the passengers' praise, Schornstheimer said his
son's actions were all in a day's work.
   ``He's pretty calm under pressure,'' he said. ``He said he was
calm and did what needed to be done, just like any other pilot
would have. They were talking about it on TV like (he was a hero),
but he said he just did what any other pilot would have done in the
same circumstance. But of course, he's skillful enough and trained
well enough to do it.''
   Passengers also praised other crew members.
   ``Make sure you tell them about the stewardesses,'' one
passenger told a reporter while being wheeled into Maui Memorial
Hospitl for treatment.
   One flight attendant crawled along the aisle, calming passengers
and trying to help the passengers put on their life vests, said
entertainer Robert Lopaka Brown, who was returning from his
honeymoon.
   ``Everyone went to work to better their chances of surviving a
crash,'' he said.
</TEXT>
