<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TurnpikeExplosives     04-30 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turnpike Explosives,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kunstler: Deck Stacked Against Suspected Japanese Terrorist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese man linked to a terrorist group
traveled about 7,000 miles in the month before he was arrested on
charges of carrying three powerful pipe bombs in his car, according
to federal documents.
   Yu Kikumura, 35, pleaded innocent Friday to all charges on the
12-count federal indictment. He was arrested April 12 along the New
Jersey Turnpike and is being held without bond in New York City.
   His lawyer, William Kunstler, accused federal prosecutors of
creating an atmosphere of hysteria and paranoia by trying to link
Kikumura to the left-wing Japanese Red Army terrorist group.
   ``I'm not saying we can win on all counts,'' Kunstler told
reporters outside the courtroom. ``They made it so unfair to start
with.''
   ``There's been a lot of innuendo about Mr. Kikumura causing a
great deal of prejudice,'' Kunstler told U.S. District Judge Alfred
J. Lechner Jr. ``References to the Red Army are bad in a country
already fearful of terrorism.''
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. dismissed Kunstler's charges.
   ``This case has a lot of international implications and we have
had some contact with foreign police agencies,'' Alito said later
in a telephone interview. ``I'm quite sure that he'll be able to
get a fair trial.''
   The Japanese foreign ministry has said it suspects Kikumura of
being a member of the Red Army, which was blamed for the recent
bombing of a USO club in Naples, Italy. Authorities have said they
are investigating whether Kikumura was linked to the group.
   Court documents filed Friday revealed new details about
Kikumura's activities in the United States.
   The documents said Kikumura traveled about 7,000 miles between
March 14 and his arrest April 12, staying in numerous hotels and
motels and in a trailer at a West Virginia campground.
   The FBI filed a request to thoroughly search Kikumura's car, and
said three mechanics at a New York auto dealership reported seeing
a revolver when Kikumura brought his brown Mazda in for servicing
March 14.
   No gun was found during a search of the interior, and
authorities suspect it may be in a hidden compartment.
   Kunstler hugged Kikumura when federal marshals brought the
defendant into the courtroom in leg irons and handcuffs.
   The lawyer and his associate, Ronald Kuby, said federal
attorneys, motivated by political considerations against suspected
leftists, built up the number of counts by charging Kikumura for
each pipe bomb he allegedly carried.
   ``This is virtually a triple indictment,'' Kunstler said.
Authorities say Kikumura would face a 90-year sentence if convicted
on all 12 counts, which also include charges involving
improprieties with a passport and a visa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
