<DOCNO> AP880430-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0636EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-30 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Ease Over Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms swirled through the lower Mississippi Valley today
after hitting central Texas with baseball-sized hail and 11
tornadoes that uprooted palm trees, overturned trailers and ripped
roofs from several homes.
   There were no reports of serious injury. Most of the damage
Friday was near Corpus Christi and San Antonio, where wind tossed
trash cans through windows, toppled power poles and damaged cars.
   ``I saw it. There's no question in my mind. It was not a major
tornado, but it was a regular one. It was loaded with stuff and it
was doing its zig zag around,'' said Bill Easley, whose 4-month-old
daughter suffered a leg cut when a traffic light smashed through
his windshield.
   The thunderstorms swept across the lower Mississippi Valley
early this morning, but there were no reports of severe weather.
   Other thunderstorms were reported over the central Gulf Coast
region early today, bringing heavy rain. A flash flood watch was
posted for southwestern Louisiana.
   Meanwhile, a cold front crossing the western United States
brought snow and strong wind to some areas. A snow advisory was
posted for the Cascade Mountains of Oregon, the mountains and
foothills of southwestern Montana, and the mountains east of the
Continental Divide.
   Today's forecast called for showers extending from New York
across northern New England; rain and snow in the mountains from
the upper Missouri Valley across the northern Rockies and the
northern Pacific coast; showers and thunderstorms from southeast
Texas across the central Gulf of Mexico coast through Florida,
southwest Georgia and much of Alabama; winds strong and gusty over
the Rockies and southern California.
   High temperatures were expected in the 50s and 60s from New
England across the Virginias, the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley,
from the Rockies to the Pacific coast; in the 90s over the desert
southwest and in the 70s and 80s over the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 29
degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 78 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 53 cloudy; Boston 43 foggy; Buffalo 43 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 53 fair; Cincinnati 45 fair; Cleveland 45 partly
cloudy; Detroit 46 fair; Miami 75 fair; New York 46 rain;
Philadelphia 45 rain; Pittsburgh 43 cloudy; Portland, Maine 41
foggy; Washington 49 rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 56 partly cloudy; Chicago 48 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 60 cloudy; Denver 55 fair; Des Moines 51 fair;
Indianapolis 41 fair; Kansas City 55 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 53
fair; Nashville 44 fair; New Orleans 60 rain; St. Louis 53 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 57 fair; Anchorage 40 showery; Las Vegas 68
fair; Los Angeles 60 fair; Phoenix 75 fair; Salt Lake City 63
windy; San Diego 61 fair; San Francisco 53 windy; Seattle 41 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 41 cloudy; Toronto 41 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
