<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Cartoon     04-30 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Cartoon,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Protests Cartoon in Los Angeles Times</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sevannah Meryn in 2nd graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Teddy Kollek sent a telegram to The Los
Angeles Times protesting a cartoon published in the paper that
depicts Jesus being turned away from Jerusalem by Israeli troops,
the mayor's spokeswoman said.
   In the telegram, sent earlier this week, Kollek objected to the
implication Israeli authorities closed Jerusalem to non-Jews,
spokeswoman Sevannah Meryn said Friday.
   ``In all its history, Jerusalem has never been freer or more
open to visitors to holy places as it is now,'' Meryn quoted the
telegram as saying. ``Half a million Christians visit Jerusalem
each year, as well as some 120,000 Moslems from countries
technically at war with Israel.
   ``Even though a cartoon is only a cartoon, it must be based on
some reality, and not only on doubtful, hostile impressions and
opinions,'' it said.
   The cartoon by the newspaper's Paul Conrad, published March 30,
shows Jesus arriving at the gate to Jerusalem on a donkey, followed
by several robed figures holding palm branches. An Israeli soldier
blocks his path, saying: ``Jerusalem is a closed military area!''
   The cartoon was an apparent reference to the frequent closures
imposed by the military in the occupied territories in an effort to
quell the 5-month-old Arab uprising.
   Israel radio said the cartoon was one of two that angered
Israel's consul general in Los Angeles, Eitan Ben Tzur. The radio
said Ben Tzur proposed to the Foreign Ministry that Israel revoke
the press credentials of the Los Angeles Times reporter in Israel,
Dan Fisher.
   Yossi Beilin, the ministry's director general, was quoted as
calling the proposal a ``stupid idea'' because Fisher had nothing
to do with the cartoons.
   The second cartoon, published April 27, depicts an Israeli
soldier holding a smoking rifle standing atop a pile of
bullet-ridden bodies. The caption reads: ``I'm willing to talk
peace, but there aren't any Palestinians to talk peace with!''
</TEXT>
