<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sinkhole     04-30 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sinkhole,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Sinkhole Swallows 1 Home, Threatens 2 Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEBRING, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large sinkhole quickly swallowed a house
and two others teetered on the edge in a subdivision near this
central Florida town, authorities said today.
   Just two hours after it opened Friday evening, the hole had
grown to 70 yards wide and 15 feet deep, witnesses and officials
said. No injuries were reported, Highlands County sheriff's
dispatcher Kathy Buchanan said.
   ``Every once in a while you can hear a crack'' as it widens,
said John Davis, a 15-year-old who lives a few blocks from the
sinkhole. The first home was completely in the hole.
   The sinkhole also swallowed a garage and was expanding toward
two homes next door, Ms. Buchanan said.
   ``The roof's almost even with the road around it,'' Davis said.
   Dr. Barry Beck, a geologist in Orlando who directs the Florida
Sinkhole Research Institute at the University of Central Florida,
said he was surprised to see a large sinkhole in the area.
   ``We rarely if ever get any that far south,'' he said.
   Sinkholes are largely caused by the altering of the water table
in the limestone and clay under the soil, experts say.
   A sudden lowering of the water table because of irrigation or
drought can weaken and collapse underground limestone caverns,
while too much water draining into the ground can dissolve
clay-like materials and rock below.
</TEXT>
