<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Helmsleys     04-30 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helmsleys,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sept. 14 Trial Date Set for Helmsleys' Tax Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire real estate magnate Harry B.
Helmsley and his ``hotel queen'' wife, Leona, will stand trial on
federal tax charges before facing a similar state indictment, a
prosecutor says.
   U.S. District Judge John Walker set a Sept. 14 tentative trial
date Friday after Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita said the
judge presiding over the Helmsley case in state court had agreed to
let the federal trial go first.
   Helmsley, 79, and his 67-year-old wife were indicted April 15 on
state and federal charges of disguising about $4 million in
renovations to their Greenwich, Conn., mansion as business expenses
and taking bogus tax deductions.
   The Helmsleys have pleaded innocent to both the 188-count state
indictment and the 47-count federal indictment.
   According to the indictments, the Helmsleys allegedly spent the
$4 million to refurbish their mansion with an enclosure for one of
the estate's two pools; a breakfast room and marble dance floor on
the roof of that enclosure; an elaborate indoor-outdoor stereo
system; more than $370,000 in landscaping; and an assortment of
furniture and paintings.
</TEXT>
