<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Refusenik     04-30 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Refusenik,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refusenik Told He Can Visit Ailing Wife in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish refusenik said today he had been told he
will be given permission to leave the Soviet Union temporarily to
visit his wife in an American hospital.
   Vladimir Tufeld, 60, said he was called to the Ministry of
General Machine-Building Friday and told he should be able to
receive his passport on Tuesday or Wednesday.
   The ministry has objected to the former electrical engineer's
emigration on the basis that it could damage state security. But
Tufeld said the work the ministry cites is 15 years old.
   He first applied to emigrate in 1977.
   Tufeld's 57-year-old wife, Izolda, was granted permission in
late December to travel to the United States to be treated for a
brain tumor. She is hospitalized at the Johns Hopkins Hospital in
Baltimore, where she has had several operations.
   The couple's son Igor, who emgrated to Israel a decade ago, went
to Baltimore to be with his mother.
   In a telephone call to The Associated Press, Tufeld said he
planned to leave as soon as possible upon completing the Soviet
paperwork.
   The ministry did not know for how long his visa would be valid,
he said.
   Tufeld said he also planned to seek medical treatment while in
the United States. Doctors have told him he suffers from gallstones
and either a herniated disc or a tumor in his back, but Soviet
diagnostic equipment cannot distinguish which it is.
   Tufeld said the decision to allow him to leave the Soviet Union
temporarily showed the inconsistency of Soviet policy. If he does
hold information that could compromise Soviet security, there would
be no sense allowing him to travel abroad, he said.
   Emigration has increased recently, but does not approach the
level of 1979, when more than 51,000 Soviet Jews left the country.
</TEXT>
