<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand-Politics     04-30 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Politics,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislation To Protect U.S. Copyrights Voided After Parliament
Dissolved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dissolution of Parliament has
voided a controversial bill to protect U.S. copyrights, a legal
expert said today.
   Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda dissolved his Cabinet and the
House of Representatives on Friday after political infighting over
the legislation. Elections have been scheduled for July 24.
   Kramol Thongdhamchart of Bangkok's Chulalongkorn University said
the bill would have to be reconsidered by the next government since
it had not passed through several required steps before becoming
law.
   On Thursday, the House voted 183-134 to protect U.S. copyrights
of artistic and literary works which are widely pirated in
Thailand. The United States had indicated it might retaliate
economically if the measure did not pass.
   The bill still needed approval by the Senate and King Bhumibol
Adulyadej, the country's constitutional monarch, before becoming
law, Kramol said.
   Supporters of the 67-year-old Prem, who has served since 1980,
said the action was taken because political dissidents refused to
``play by the rules of the democratic game.''
   Political opponents criticized the prime minister for avoiding a
probable no-confidence motion in Parliament next month.
   Sixteen ministers of the Democrat Party _ the main party of
Prem's coalition government _ resigned Friday after failing to stop
party dissidents from voting against the government-backed
copyright bill. The dissidents said the legislation would force
Thailand to bow to American bullying.
   The United States had indicated it would cut tax privileges of
Thai imports if the copyright bill was rejected.
   Radio Thailand today quoted a senior government official as
saying 357 House seats would be contested in the upcoming general
election, 10 more than in the last one in 1986. Representation in
the lower house is based on population.
   Anak Sitthiprasart, director-general of the Local Administration
Department, was quoted as saying that the polling would cost $9.9
million.
   Prem, a former army general, is credited with providing Thailand
with political stability after years of coups and rapid government
changes.
</TEXT>
