<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Alert     04-30 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Alert,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Detained In Alert Against Palestinian Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGELES CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police detained an Iraqi and an
Iranian while searching for Palestinian terrorists reportedly
planning to bomb a U.S. air base and hangouts of American
servicemen, officials said today.
   Police also picked up two bearded foreigners but released them
when they turned out to be an off-duty American serviceman and an
Australian tourist, the officials said.
   The roundups occurred late Friday and today. Police and soldiers
in this city 50 miles north of Manila remained on alert following a
report that terrorists planned to bomb Clark Air Base and bars
frequented by Americans.
   Lt. Col. Victor Signey, chief of the Philippine Constabulary's
Angeles command, said Iraqi Kamil Shariff Babi, 32, and Iranian
Ghesan Shooat Bakhsh, 32, were picked up from two buses from Manila
which soldiers stopped at a checkpoint Friday night.
   The two were detained because they could present no passports to
prove their identities, Signey said. They were not charged.
   Signey said he wanted to verify the authenticity of a U.N.
document Babi presented showing he was a political refugee.
   ``We don't know why they arrested and locked us up here,'' Babi
told reporters in his cell. ``They can verify my status with the
Department of Foreign Affairs.''
   Bakhsh said he was a medical student and his passport was
confiscated by immigration authorities in Manila.
   Angeles City police chief Lt. Col. Orlando Macaspac told
reporters the report from the Israeli intelligence service Mossad
said the bombings were to be carried out by at least eight
Palestinians.
   Spokesmen for both the Israeli and U.S. embassies said they had
no knowledge of the purported Israeli intelligence report.
   American authorities had stepped up security at Clark, Subic
Naval Base and four smaller installations after communist rebels
killed three Americans and a Filipino near Clark last October.
</TEXT>
