<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0838EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Priest-Cocaine     04-30 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Priest-Cocaine,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuelan Police Detain Cocaine-Smuggling Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest who police say was caught
with 46 pounds of cocaine said Satan tempted him to sell narcotics
but that he used the profits to help the poor.
   Intelligence Police Commissioner Osvaldo Granadillo said Friday
the Spanish-born Venezuelan priest, Jose Luis Gil Fernandez, 57,
was arrested at Maiquetia International Airport outside Caracas
Wednesday night after police found the cocaine packed in his
suitcases.
   Gil Fernandez, who for 24 years has been the parish priest at
San Mateo, 36 miles west of Caracas, was headed for Madrid.
   A former priest, Juan Rojano Martinez, 54, and his wife Graciela
Ramos de Rojano, 46, were arrested hours later in Caracas and are
alleged to have drawn Gil Fernandez into the smuggling trade,
Granadillo said.
   ``I wouldn't say that the Venezuelan church has been penetrated
by traffickers, but (Gil Fernandez) is a priest and he is involved
in drug-running,'' Granadillo said in a phone interview.
   The priest told reporters Thursday that he had smuggled cocaine
to Madrid on two previous occasions.
   He acknowledged he was paid $9,000 for the first cargo of 19
pounds in 1984 and $32,000 for a second load of about 30 pounds. He
did not say when the second operation took place.
   The 46-pound cargo would have netted him $50,000, he said.
   ``I gave it all to the church,'' Gil Fernandez said. ``I paid
for a new chapel in San Mateo, a parish boarding school, and
decorations for the church altar, and I helped out the children who
needed the money so much. I haven't got a penny of it.
   ``I repent and I want to die ... I was tempted by Satan and I
know the damage I have done to the church and I deserve
punishment,'' he said.
   He said Rojano had pressured him to carry the drugs and that he
had asked his church superiors in March to remove him from the
parish ``because I was horribly afraid.''
   Fathe Amador Merino, spokesman for the Venezuelan Episcopal
Conference, said Friday that the church is ``disconcerted and full
of consternation and pain'' over the case.
   ``The church does not judge and will let (Venezuelan) justice
follow its course,'' Merino said.
   ``In (Gil Fernandez's) confusion and good faith, I think he
believed that this was the best use for the money made from this
nefarious trafficking business,'' he said.
   He said top Venezuela church officials visited Gil Fernandez on
Thursday ``to be close to him in these moments of confusion.''
   He said didn't know of any other cases of Venezuelan church
officials involved in drug smuggling.
   Granadillo said the priest's activities had been under
observation for over a year.
   Police said formal charges wilt be drawn up against the priest
and the Rojano couple next week.
   Drug smuggling in Venezuela carries a jail sentence of six to
thirty years, the nation's maximum penalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
