<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea-Bomb     04-30 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Bomb,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Headquarters Attacked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four protesters hurled homemade bombs
today at the headquarters of President Roh Tae-woo's governing
party, police said. There were no injuries.
   The crude bombs, made from plastic milk bottles, exploded in the
driveway of the Democratic Justice Party headquarters. The
protesters scattered leaflets charging that the December
presidential elections were rigged.
   Paek In-sung, 23, of Dongkuk University in Seoul was arrested
for allegedly taking part in the attack, police said. Three other
suspects fled.
   ``Down with the DJP which stole the will of the people in
elections,'' police quoted Paek as shouting before his arrest.
   Police later identified Paek as a member of the
``Save-the-Nation Suicide Squad,'' which organized the seizure of a
library in the U.S Cultural Center building in Seoul on Feb. 24.
Paek was sought in connection with the case.
   Five members of the radical student group stormed the center's
second-floor library to protest Washington's support for Roh.
   Roh won the Dec. 16 election when two opposition candidates
split the anti-Roh vote. Roh's governing party lost its majority in
the National Assembly during legislative elections last week.
</TEXT>
