<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Church 1stLd-Writethru   04-30 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Church, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0473,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev, In Rare Meeting With Church Leaders, Asks Their Backing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS three grafs with background on possible visit by pope.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a rare and highly publicized Kremlin meeting
with Russian Orthodox Church leaders, Mikhail S. Gorbachev promised
greater religious tolerance and sought support for his drive for
domestic change.
   The Soviet leader also condemned past repression of religious
activity.
   He said a law now being drafted on ``freedom of conscience''
will reflect the ``tangible results of new approaches to
state-church relations in the conditions of perestroika
(restructuring) and democratization.''
   Friday's meeting was Gorbachev's first with high church
officials since he became Communist Party chief in March 1985. Such
a meeting is unusual because party doctrine professes atheism.
   The encounter, reported by the official news agency Tass, was
the lead item on the evening news program ``Vremya'' and a front
page story in today's editions of Pravda and other Soviet dailies.
   Tass said church head Patriarch Pimen had requested the meeting
with the Communist Party chief to discuss the June celebration of
the 1,000th anniversary of Christianity's arrival in Russia.
   Gorbachev said his campaign for the restructuring of society
offers benefits to religious believers but also carries obligations
that can be met during the 1,000th anniversary celebration.
   `On the eve of this event I would like to express the desire
that it is marked by the consolidation of our country's believers,
all working people, for the sake of our common great cause of
perestroika, of the renewal of socialism, complete unfolding of its
humanistic ethical potential,'' Tass quoted him as telling the
church leaders.
   Gorbachev has said his overhaul of society and the economy faces
opposition at many levels, so the appeal to church leaders was seen
as an effort to enlist the support of another element of Soviet
society.
   He did not specify what the new law governing religion would say
or when it would be completed, but said it would ``reflect the
interests of religious organizations.''
   The law now in effect, dating back to 1929, requires
registration of all religious groups, and prevents charitable
activities and religious education of the young.
   Archbishop Kiril of Smolensk told a news conference on March 31
that the rewriting of the law ``will open the possibility for a
fuller church life for all believers'' in the Soviet Union.
   Under Soviet power, the Russian Orthodox Church has been subject
at times to harassment and violent anti-religious campaigns. In
1961, Premier Nikita S. Khrushchev predicted the complete
elimination of religion in the Soviet Union by 1980.
   Pimen, the 77-year-old patriarch of Moscow and All Russia, told
Gorbachev that Soviet religious leaders ``ardently pray for the
success of the restructuring process, and strive to do everything
possible for its development,'' Tass said.
   However, Pimen said without elaborating that ``not all problems
of church life receive their resolution so far.''
   In his talk with the prelates, Gorbachev acknowledged the
suffering of religious believers under the late Soviet dictator
Josef V. Stalin.
   ``Mistakes made with regard to the church and believers in the
1930s and the years that followed are being rectified,'' Gorbachev
said, without referring to Stalin by name.
   Religious believers were among the millions of people killed or
imprisoned under Stalin. Churches and their property were destroyed
during Stalin's drive to establish collectives.
   Under Gorbachev, Soviet media have been reporting extensively on
Stalin's mistakes and repression.
   The millenium of Russian Christianity has raised the question of
a possible visit by Pope John Paul II. The Polish-born pontiff,
head of the Roman Catholic Church, has frequently expressed his
desire to visit Soviet Catholics, but has publicly disclosed that
he has been refused permission at least twice.
   However, a Tass official said on April 20 that changing domestic
conditions in the Soviet Union could pave the way for the pope's
first Soviet pilgrimage.
   ``I am absolutely sure that this climate (conducive to a papal
visit) is being created,'' Anatoly A. Krasikov, Tass deputy
director general, told a news conference in Rome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
