<DOCNO> AP880430-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0919EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Turkey-Assassination     04-30 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey-Assassination,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Denies Role in Armenian Terrorist's Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today denied involvement in
the assassination of a man believed to be the leader of an Armenian
terrorist group.
   The man, identified as Agop Agopian, was shot and killed
Thursday outside his home in Athens, Greece, in an attack by two
masked men.
   The group Agopian founded and led, the Armenian Secret Army for
the Liberation of Armenia, accused Turkey and ``imperialist
allies'' Friday of masterminding the killing. Greek newspapers
published similar claims.
   But Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Inal Batu today said
``such claims are absurd. Turkey never used these methods in
dealing with terrorism.''
   No one claimed responsibility for Agopian's killing.
   One report, from the Armenian Secret Army in Beirut, Lebanon,
said Agopian was fired from the organization in late 1987.
   The organization, founded in 1975, has taken responsibility for
more than 60 attacks against Turkish targets, including the
killings of about 30 Turkish diplomats and dependents in western
Europe and the United States. His group said it carried out the
July 1983 bombing of the Turkish Airlines desk at Orly Airport in
Paris that killed eight people and injured 56.
   The Marxist organization seeks an independent Armenian state in
eastern Turkey. It also demands vengeance for what it says was the
massacre of 1.5 million Armenians by Ottoman Turks in 1915-1916.
   Turkish officials acknowledge 300,000 Armenians died after
Ottoman Empire officials deported the country's 1.4 million
Armenians to Syria during World War I.
   Independent historians say at least 600,000 Armenians died on
the trip.
</TEXT>
