<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland-Prisoners 1stLd-Writethru   04-30 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Prisoners, 1st Ld-Writethru,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Released Labor Leaders Refuse To Leave Poland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with comments from family. Pick
up graf 7 `Morawiecki, who...'
^With PM-Poland, Bjt</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today released two former
underground Solidarity leaders from prison in a secret deal with
Roman Catholic church officials, but the activists refused to leave
the country, family members said.
   Witnesses and relatives said the two were then returned to a
Warsaw prison, but their status remained unclear. A spokesman for
the communist government declined comment.
   The two, Kornel Morawiecki and Andrzej Kolodziej, were driven to
Warsaw's airport to board a flight to Rome, but they decided to
stay in Poland after meeting with family members.
   The two were released from Warsaw's Rakowiecka prison early
today in an apparent deal between the Roman Catholic church and
communist authorities. Both men were leaders of a militant
Solidarity splinter group.
   They were given multiple exit-and-entry passports and were
supposed to go to Rome for unspecified medical treatment.
   But after meeting with relatives in an airport lounge and
hearing of a new wave of strikes, they decided to stay in the
country, relatives said.
   ``They are staying,'' Morawiecki's daughter, Anna, told
reporters at the airport. ``They may go at a later date, but they
want to think it over.''
   Morawiecki and Kolodziej were driven back from the airport in
two umarked cars. Witnesses who followed said they were returned to
Rakowiecka prison by security officials.
   Also present at the airport meeting were three priests from the
episcopate and a lawyer. The priests declined to comment.
   Speaking later to reporters in Warsaw, Morawiecki's daughter
said she was surprised that the two men were taken back to prison.
   ``At first, they agreed to go (abroad). But there was no
ultimatum,'' she said. ``They wanted to talk to the families, to
consult with each other, because they had no such opportunity in
prison.''
   She said the two men wanted at least 24 hours to make up their
minds.
   Ewa Maria Stoja, Kolodziej's girlfriend, said official documents
indicated the two men were being released at the recommendation of
a commission of prison doctors ``due to the required urgent medical
examination, which may also take place abroad.''
   The two women said Kolodziej suffered from ulcers and teeth
problems, while Morawiecki had ulcer symptoms, poor eyesight, and
heart and kidney ailments.
   Anna Morawiecka said the release of the two men was arranged by
church officials and that there had been ``some intervention'' by
Pope John Paul II.
   Morawiecki, who was was arrested Nov. 9, was chairman of the
militant splinter group Fighting Solidarity.
   He had been in hiding since the December 1981 martial law
crackdown on the labor group Solidarity. The next year, he formed
Fighting Solidarity, which differs from the outlawed independent
labor federation because it advocates anti-communist political
goals. Solidarity emphasizes social and union issues.
   Kolodziej headed Fighting Solidarity from the time of
Morawiecki's arrest until his own capture in January. He had been
in hiding since 1985.
   Authorities alleged that the two were part of a ring that
attempted to smuggle equipment intended for terrorist use from
Sweden. They were never formally charged.
   In a statement in November, Kolodziej denied the allegations.
   A third, less prominent Fighting Solidarity activist, Krzystof
Szymanski, was also released today.
   In another development, Jan Andrzej Gorny, the Solidarity leader
in the southern Silesian industrial region, was released after an
appeals court on Friday suspended his sentence, Solidarity sources
said.
   Gorny was serving an 18-month sentence at a prison in Katowice
after being convicted of failing to pay alimony and using false
identity cards.
   In September 1986, the government of Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
issued a broad amnesty for political prisoners. Since then, the
political activists it has jailed have been held on criminal
charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
