<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TuskegeeProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0502 04-30 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tuskegee Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Temporary Restraining Order Against University</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `University officials...', to CORRECT judge's
name to Bryan, sted Bryant.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TUSKEGEE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's decision to throw out his
temporary restraining order against Tuskegee University means
students who owe the school more than $300 will not be allowed to
take final exams next week.
   Macon County Circuit Judge Howard F. Bryan had halted the
predominantly black private school's crackdown Wednesday. But after
a six-hour hearing Friday, Bryan dissolved the order.
   University officials estimate there are 600 students who owe
more than $300 each, and argued that Bryan's original order had
hampered their ability to collect. Students said the crackdown was
issued without adequate notice and threatened those students who
were having financial difficulties.
   University President Benjamin Payton said he was ``deeply
saddened that it was necessary to go to this length to make that
point.''
   ``This is not a case of Tuskegee University fighting its
students,'' he said. ``It's a case of Tuskegee University insisting
that students learn very important lessons for life.''
   Bryan ordered the school to leave its business office open over
the weekend so students can make payments before exams begin Monday.
   The university's crackdown on overdue fees had sparked a week of
protests, including a sit-in at the administration building last
weekend.
   Michael Pintard, president of the Student Government
Association, said the ruling was a ``serious miscarriage of
justice.''
   Pintard said university officials should have identified
``categories of students'' who couldn't make payments because of
financial difficulties, and worked out a timetable for those
students.
   Bryan said he agreed with the students' complaints on a personal
level, adding, ``Prohibiting students from attending class is an
exceedingly drastic action, with as little notice as was given.''
   But he said he had no legal grounds to stop the school policy
because the students didn't show that the university's policy was
arbitrary or would irreparably injure them.
</TEXT>
