<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghan-Soviet Bjt   04-30 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Soviet, Bjt,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Buffer Zone Emerging Despite Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY12</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union says it will withdraw Red Army
troops from Afghanistan, but it appears that the Kremlin is
creating a buffer zone along the Soviet border in the northern
Afghan area. Here is a report from the area.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MAZAR-E-SHARIF, Afghanistan (AP) _ A northern strip of
Afghanistan, rich in agriculture and natural resources, is being
transformed into a Soviet buffer zone, despite the planned
withdrawal of Red Army troops.
   All nine Afghan provinces bordering the Soviet Union recently
were grouped to form a new ``Northern Zone'' with a de facto
capital in Mazar-e-Sharif, ostensibly to coordinate development
programs.
   Virtually isolated from the rest of Afghanistan by the towering
Hindu Kush mountains, the ethnic minorities of the north are closer
in language and culture to the Soviets across the border than to
their fellow Afghans in the south.
   ``For several months, there has been an escalation of
Sovietization of the north,'' a foreign diplomat in Kabul said.
``Thousands of young people have gone to school in the Soviet
Union. Some come home with Russian wives. It's a very classical
colonization.''
   The diplomat, who spoke on condition he not to be identified
further, said the Soviet military withdrawal does not mean the
Kremlin is abandoning Afghanistan while President Najib's
government is still under attack by U.S.-supplied guerrillas.
   ``The Soviets do not want to lose Afghanistan. The north is a
Soviet zone,'' he said.
   He noted that the ``Northern Zone'' includes Faryab province,
the Afghan oil region, and said Faryab ``is already completely
dominated by the Soviet Union.''
   The Soviets have pledged to start withdrawing their 115,000
soldiers from Afghanistan on May 15 under a U.N.-mediated accord
signed with the United States two weeks ago in Geneva.
   Mazar-e-Sharif, the administrative center of Balkh province,
sits on a flat plain 40 miles from the Amu River that forms the
Soviet border.
   Almost every car in the dusty town is Soviet-made. Shop names
are written in the Russian alphabet as well as in the
Arabic-Persian script used by Afghanistan. Soviet-style posters
extolling the virtues of work and socialism loom over the streets.
   Early this year, references to the new ``Northern Zone'' started
appearing in speeches and newspaper articles in Kabul, the Afghan
capital.
   ``The main point behind such rearrangement was to coordinate
projects and needs, because this area enjoys rich natural resources
_ gas, coal, others,'' said Mohammad Sharif, secretary of the Balkh
province central committee of the People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan.
   Afghan officials quickly point out that other Afghan provinces
also have been grouped into regional zones. But only the ``Northern
Zone'' has its own deputy prime minister.
   Najibullah Masir, minister of mines and industry and former head
of the Afghan-Soviet Friendship Society, was named to the post two
months ago.
   Mazar-e-Sharif and Kabul, 180 miles south of the border, are
expected to be the last cities vacated by Soviet troops before the
Feb. 15, 1989, deadline for final withdrawal.
   According to Afghan and Western observers who spoke on condition
of anonymity, Mazar-e-Sharif is one of the most pacified areas of
the country.
   In 1987 the official Soviet news media acknowledged that
anti-Soviet guerrillas had launched at least two attacks across the
border on Soviet soil. According to a U.S. State Department
publication, the Soviets retaliated with attacks that caused
``enormous'' civilian casualties.
   Sharif said the Soviet-backed Afghan government now controls all
but 80 of the 433 villages in Balkh province. These figures could
not be verified, but 18 months ago Afghan officials said only half
the villages were under government control.
   The nine northern provinces have an estimated 2 million to 3
million inhabitants, about one-fourth of Afghanistan's total
population.
   Nearly all the people belong to the Uzbek, Kirghiz, Tajik and
Turkmen tribes _ the same ethnic minorities who live across the
border in the Soviet republics of Uzbekistan, Kirghizia, Tajikistan
and Turkmenistan.
   Western sources in Kabul say they strongly doubt the guerrillas,
or Islamic holy warriors, can take control of Kabul. But if it does
happen, they say the northern zone could serve as a refuge and
restaging area for the Najib government.
   ``If the situation is very bad in Kabul, the government could go
to the north for reconquest,'' a non-American diplomat said. ``But
I should be very surprised if Kabul falls. I think Kabul will be
very well-defended by the Afghan army with Soviet advisers.''
</TEXT>
