<DOCNO> AP880430-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-QuestionTime Bjt   04-30 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Question Time, Bjt,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Question-Time: A Twice-Weekly 15-Minute Verbal Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 3.15 p.m. most Tuesdays and Thursdays, Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher marches into Parliament for one of
Britain's liveliest political traditions _ Question Time.
   Armed with a thick notebook of statistics, she jousts with
questioning lawmakers amid the roar of others frantic to make a
point. Fifteen minutes later she departs, and the House of Commons
begins its business for the day.
   The public gallery is packed for Question Time, and millions
more hear the rhetorical fireworks later on radio and TV. Starting
this fall, they'll be able to see the action, too, following a
Commons decision to let in television cameras.
   Born in 1721 to allow lawmakers to obtain information, Question
Time has developed into a test of ministerial mettle and, some say,
a publicity show. In 1901 a House leader called it a ``scandal,''
and today, many say it is more furious than ever.
   ``It's turned into a kind of gladiatorial battle,'' says London
School of Economics Professor Alan Beattie, a specialist in
Parliament. ``It's very noisy and very crude.''
   ``It's become a waste of time,'' says Tam Dalyell, a Laborite
expelled from the House for five days last year for calling Mrs.
Thatcher a ``liar'' in Parliament. ``It's hullabaloo.''
   The curtain rises on Question Time, a mixture of ancient pomp
and modern informality, as 62-year-old Mrs. Thatcher takes her seat
on the government side of the House. Lawmakers lounging on their
green leather pew-like benches sit up, alert.
   Question from Ron Davies of the opposition Labor Party:
   ``In her endeavor to re-establish the bonds of family life, has
the prime minister ever given any consideration to the value of a
wife? Is she aware that the Forestry Commission ... is offering in
compensation two pounds ($3.80) per week for each keeper's wife?
   ``Given that the Forestry Commission pays the same keepers 45
pence (85 cents) a week for a ferret and 2.30 pounds ($4.37) a week
for a dog, should she not intervene?''
   Mrs. Thatcher replies: ``I think the honorable gentleman will be
aware that the budget set out considerably to help wives ... We on
this side value them very highly.''
   The sound and fury rises steadily, and by the time Labor leader
Neil Kinnock begins criticizing Mrs. Thatcher's welfare reforms,
the prime minister's voice is barely audible.
   She calls Kinnock's remarks ``utterly futile,'' as lawmakers
scream ``Answer the Question!,'' ``You're Wrong!'' and Speaker of
the House Bernard Weatherill cries ``Order! Order!''
   Mrs. Thatcher relies heavily on statistics for her replies,
while some of her predecessors have preferred barbed repartee.
   The late Winston Churchill was once asked: ``Is the prime
minister aware of the deep concern felt by the people of this
country at the whole question of the Korean conflict?'' To which
Churchill sniffed: ``I am well aware of the deep concern felt by
the honorable member in many matters above his comprehension.''
   Mrs. Thatcher's near-decade in power has led to frustration in
opposition ranks, and her personality has caused more friction than
perhaps any other British leader, Beattie says.
   ``The strategy she adopts is that you don't worry if the
opposition hates you, you worry about whether your own side thinks
you've won,'' says Beattie. Some say speakers tolerate more
disorder both in debate and Question Time to ensure the protection
of minority party rights, but that tolerance has led to increased
unruliness throughout the House.
   One of the worst recent incidents occurred not during Question
Time but at the end of a dramatic debate on taxation.
   In a show of anti-Thatcher rage, Labor hard-liner Ron Brown
dropped and dented the gold and silver mace, the club that is a
symbol of royal authority in the chamber. He was expelled for 20
working days after refusing to apologize.
   However, Weatherill says he feels that generally ``the House
proceeds in good order.''
   He told the British Broadcasting Corp. he also believes Question
Time may quiet down when television enters the chamber for six
months this fall.
   ``I think the new stars are likely to be the reasonable
members,'' he said.
   Opponents argue that TV will encourage showing off. Strathclyde
University in Scotland has offered to teach lawmakers how to
perform for television for $285 a day but says no one has signed up.
</TEXT>
