<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-English     04-30 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-English,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Calls For New Standards For English Teaching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The birthplace of English had better mind its p's
and q's and improve its English teaching methods at the same time,
according to a government study which criticizes how the language
is taught in Great Britain.
   The study, released Friday by a government-appointed committee,
concluded that most English teachers in Britain were not properly
equipped for the job and recommended that many be retrained.
   Education Secretary Kenneth Baker welcomed the report. He said
his department will incorporate its recommendations into a new
curriculum planned by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservative government in a major shake-up of the nation's
educational system.
   ``Most schools no longer teach old-fashioned grammar. But little
has been put in its place,'' Baker said last year when he
established the committee to study the situation.
   The 90-page report follows a yearlong inquiry by the committee
into how English is taught in Britain. Panel members include Peter
Levi, professor of poetry at Oxford University; novelists Antonia
Byatt and Keith Waterhouse; broadcaster Robert Robinson; and poet
P.J. Kavanagh. They visited schools across the nation before
writing the report.
   The report says all teachers should be trained in English and
that each school should have a teacher whose sole job is to ensure
that the language is used properly.
   It adds that national standards should be established to be met
by children at the ages of seven, 11 and 16. However, the committee
rejected a return to memorizing grammar rules.
   ``We're not anxious to go back to the idea that you simply learn
these things by rote, because all the evidence is that that doesn't
in fact improve the effectiveness of the children's use of the
language,'' said Sir John Kingman, vice-chancellor of Bristol
University and head of the committee.
   Kingman rejected the notion that the new standards would
discriminate against pupils from ethnic minority groups.
   Of Britain's 56 million people, about 2.45 million are
non-whites, mostly immigrants from Asia, Africa and the Caribbean
whose children were born and raised in Britain.
   ``The fact that they may speak a different language at home is
irrelevant, because the English language is the way they become
full members of English society,'' Kingman said.
   ``It is a way of ensuring that we do not have an underclass of
non-English speakers who are cut off from getting a job and having
a career.''
   The opposition Labor Party and the 184,400-member National Union
of Teachers also welcomed the report.
   But Michael Simon, head of the Inner London Education
Authority's English Center, said he was concerned about the notion
that all pupils must conform to a standard form of English.
   ``About 80 percent of pupils do not speak standard English
although they speak something very close to it. Any attempt to get
kids to speak standard English will just disable them as
speakers,'' he said.
   Kingman, a mathematician, said English teachers were not being
trained well in Britain and that children were suffering.
   ``We take a fairly dim view of English teacher training,'' he
said.
   The report said that by age 7, children should read passages of
simple sentences, understand the spoken language, spell common
words and write legibly; by 11, they should use punctuation and
paragraphs, argue their case on an issue and be aware of dialects.
   It said 16-year-olds should be able to express feelings, ideas
and arguments in writing and speech, make comparisions between
English and other languages and use technical terms to describe
language.
   English is the first language of 320 million people around the
world and is spoken daily by about a billion people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880430-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Professor-Prostitution     04-30 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Professor-Prostitution,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Professor Accused Of Running House Of Prostitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college professor who once claimed to
operate the ``cleanest massage parlor in California'' has been
charged with conspiracy to maintain a house of prostitution, law
enforcement officials said.
   Hal Mintz, chairman of the business department at East Los
Angeles College, is to be arraigned Thursday on the prostitution
charge and two counts of income tax evasion, according to Deputy
District Attorney Eldon Fox.
   The tax charges accuse Mintz of failing to file a return with
the state Franchise Tax Board for 1985 and 1986. Financial records
seized at his home in San Marino indicate he earned at least
$200,000 each of those years, Fox said Friday.
   Mintz's attorney, Anthony Glassman, said his client would plead
innocent to the conspiracy charge.
   ``Hal may have been lax, he may have been negligent in some
things, but he didn't know what was going on at the massage
parlor,'' Glassman said.
   The attorney said that while Mintz had not filed state tax
returns for 1985 and 1986, he was in the process of doing so when
his records were seized.
   The Beverly Hills Massage Parlor, located across the street from
the West Hollywood City Hall, adjacent to upscale Beverly Hills,
was closed in February after authorities said it was being used as
a house of prostitution.
   Six former employees of the massage parlor have agreed to
testify against Mintz in return for immunity from prosecution, Fox
said.
   A spokesman for the Los Angeles County Community College
District said the district is evaluating Mintz's position at the
college.
   ``Under the terms of the state Education Code, the particular
charge against Mintz does not enable us to automatically suspend
him,'' said Warren Kinsler, the district's general counsel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880430-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-HowDukakisDidIt Bjt   04-30 1213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-How Dukakis Did It, Bjt,1190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Early Success At Fund Raising Helped Later Victories At
Polls</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neither Michael Dukakis nor his friend and
money-raiser Bob Farmer assumed great success when they sat down at
the Massachusetts governor's breakfast table one day in the fall of
1986.
   Dukakis was casting an eye toward the presidency, and he had one
question.
   ``He said, `Look, if I decide to go for this thing, will the
money be there to wage a credible campaign?''' Farmer recalled.
   Farmer responded with some optimism, but a day later he had
second thoughts. He called Dukakis.
   ``I'm troubled by one thing,'' he told Dukakis. ``I've never
raised money for a guy who's at 1 percent in the polls.''
   As it turned out, Farmer underestimated.
   Dukakis has been underestimated all along in this presidential
campaign, much as his fall opponent, Republican George Bush, has
been.
   Critics fault Dukakis for a cold aloofness, a lack of passion,
and a presence that creates barely a ripple outside a staged event.
Not until Pennsylvania's primary Tuesday, where he won by 2-to-1
over Jesse Jackson, did polls show that as many as half those who
voted for Dukakis actually supported him strongly.
   ``This guy really is the Rodney Dangerfield of presidential
politics,'' said Bob Beckel, who managed Walter Mondale's 1984
campaign. ``This guy gets more criticism for a winner than anybody
I've seen in modern presidential politics.''
   ``Dukakis is a man who is easy to underestimate,'' says his
friend, Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton. ``But he is extremely competent
and well disciplined and has good values _ and all that comes
through to the voters.''
   Dukakis had other advantages, aside from money. He was helped by
geography and a primary calender that fit nicely with his bases of
support.
   And like any winner he was lucky. He was a beneficiary of Gary
Hart's political self-immolation, the disasters and missteps that
befell other opponents, the reluctance of New York Gov. Mario Cuomo
to enter the race, and the lack of national stature of his
opponents.
   Dukakis announced his candidacy on April 29, 1987 with a direct
shot at the then front-runner Hart and his campaign of ``new
ideas.''
   ``Ask more than whether we have new ideas,'' Dukakis said. ``Ask
whether we have already made new ideas work.''
   He called himself a long-shot when he entered the race. But
within a month all that was altered by the revelations of Hart's
relationship with a young woman.
   ``I don't think you have any real sense at the time you make
that kind of announcement what's likely to happen,'' Dukakis said
in a recent interview with The Associated Press. ``I said at the
time it's a very, very long shot. I meant it. We're all long shots.
I mean, who knows? It's a very unpredictable business.
   ``I thought that if we could organize well and raise sufficient
funds and really work at it _ as I always have _ there was a
possibility that we could do it. It's never more than a possibility
when you start.''
   Dukakis sustained his theme for a year: never mind the charisma,
here was a politician who had made government work.
   He offered as evidence the Massachusetts economic turnaround,
notwithstanding critics who said he did no more than stay out of
the way of a boom that was coming anyway.
   ``I don't think people are all that naive _ I don't think
anybody really thought he created the Massachusetts Miracle out of
whole cloth,'' said Clinton. ``But they knew that he'd been a part
of it and that he'd seen the future they wanted to achieve.''
   Dukakis campaigned in Iowa with the knowledge that he had a sure
win a week later in New Hampshire, his neighboring state. He
campaigned in the South, potentially hostile territory, by leaving
Dixie to Jackson and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. and concentrating on
atypical Southern voters: Jews and retirees in South Florida,
Hispanics in Texas, liberals throughout the region.
   He was credited with a strong organization and was able to
withstand the loss of his campaign manager and top aide, John
Sasso, in the flap over Sasso's role in campaign sabotage that
revealed Sen. Joseph Biden's plagiarism and lapses of judgment.
   He was also lucky that his third place showing in Iowa wasn't
viewed as the setback it might have been. Dukakis campaign chairman
and longtime friend Paul Brountas said his Iowa finish was
``perceived as a strong showing.''
   ``Part of the plan was to do well enough in Iowa so you could
preserve the geographic advantage you have in New Hampshire,'' he
said. ``Had he not done well in Iowa, his support in New Hampshire
may have softened.''
   Critics and supporters will argue over whether Dukakis's belated
emergence was a triumph of money over message, but it is
indisputable that his financial success made much of it possible.
   Farmer, who had been treasurer for John Glenn in 1984, initially
thought he could raise $6.5 million by the Iowa caucuses in early
February.
   His figure was in line with what the wealthiest of the other
Democrats were able to raise. But the Dukakis campaign raised $17
million by Iowa's caucus night _ a financial triumph that gave
Dukakis an enormous advantage over his rivals and paved the way for
his emergence as the likely Democratic presidential nominee.
   His bankroll allowed him to run campaigns everywhere, and to
keep staff in place while opponents were collapsing their efforts
into Iowa and New Hampshire.
   He was prepared, as a result, when the campaign moved into the
foreign territory of the South and he was able to survive
consecutive losses in Illinois and Michigan. He headed North after
Super Tuesday with $2 million in the bank, while his opponents were
broke or in debt.
   How was Dukakis able to do it and not the others? One reason was
the network Farmer built, asking not just for contributions but for
each significant donor to produce $10,000 in contributions from
their friends.
   He got enthusiastic support from Greek-Americans around the
country, tapping an igorned but often affluent community that
contributed close to one-fifth of his total.
   Importantly, Dukakis's own state had a booming economy and
active Democrats accustomed to giving.
   The race for money, in fact, can be considered one of the major
contests of 1988. And Dukakis won it going away.
   ``It isn't that candidates lose heart, it's that they run out of
money,'' Farmer said. ``Money is the winnowing factor in this
process.''
   Former rivals and current supporters alike say the critics of
his dispassionate style have missed something that voters found in
Dukakis's cool temperament.
   Mark Mellman, polltaker for Gore, said research done for that
campaign found a startlingly positive reaction among voters to
Dukakis on television, particularly in his commercials.
   He communicated, Mellman said, ``an inner strength, a quiet
passion, an intelligent commitment to substance.''
   ``That is not the typical interpretation that's put on the guy,
but I'm convinced of it from research that we have done,'' Mellman
said. ``Not sort of rip-roaring, table-thumping passion, but deep
concern and deep conviction. That speaks well of him. That
establishes a bond of trust with the voter.''
</TEXT>
