<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WaterRationing     04-30 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Rationing,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Water Rationing Begins Sunday, But Allottments Delayed For Two
Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Water rationing begins Sunday, but city
residents won't discover how much water they will be allotted for
another two weeks.
   Beginning May 15, customers will receive notices telling them
how much water they can use, the San Francisco Water Department
said Friday.
   ``We are asking people to wait until they get their allotment
before they start saying they won't have enough water. They should
wait until they know,'' said James Cooney, general manager at the
Water Department.
   ``I would encourage them to start saving water now and not panic
until they see how much they will get,'' Cooney said.
   Reduced rain and snow has lowered reservoirs from northern
California into Oregon and Washington.
   The rationing program, adopted Thursday by the city's Public
Utilities Commission, is aimed at reducing consumption by 25
percent compared with 1987.
   Among other things, the new rules prohibit washing sidewalks,
operating decorative fountains and serving water to restaurant
patrons except on request.
   The rationing program will depend on public cooperation, and the
only penalities will be increased rates for excessive use and
possible installation of flow restrictors for big wasters, said
Cooney.
</TEXT>
