<DOCNO> AP880430-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cuba-Angola     04-30 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Angola,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Builds Up Angola Forces, US Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba has quietly expanded its troop commitment
to Angola by up to 10,000 over the past five months while taking an
increasingly active role in southern Africa peace negotiations,
according to U.S. officials.
   The officials made the disclosure as Cuba, along with the United
States, South Africa and Angola, prepared for a new round of talks
on an array of southern African issues.
   The talks, scheduled for Tuesday and Wednesday in London, mark
the first time that South African and Angolan representatives have
agreed to sit at the same negotiating table to discuss a peace
settlement. The two countries have been military rivals for more
than a decade.
   Cuba had not taken a direct part in southern Africa peace
negotiations until January when Cuban officials joined Angolan
negotiators for talks with a State Department delegation in Angola.
   The U.S. officials, who asked not to be identified, said that
Cuba is believed to have had between 35,000 and 37,000 troops in
Angola as of last November. Since then 8,000 to 10,000 Cuban troops
have been sent to Angola, bringing the total to between 43,000 and
45,000, the officials said.
   This is believed to be the largest number of Cuban troops
deployed in Angola since they were first sent there in 1975 when
Angola won its independence from Portugal.
   If the Cuban and U.S. populations are compared, the current
Cuban troop commitment in Angola is proportionally far greater than
the American military involvement in Vietnam in 1968 when 525,000
U.S. servicemen _ the all-time high _ were stationed there.
   Since early March, about 5,000 Cuban troops have been sent to
the western Angolan city of Benguela, the officials said. The area
is not close to any combat zones in Angola, and U.S. officials said
Cuba's motives for the buildup are not clear.
   The Cubans generally have stayed away from combat zones in
Angola's civil war but a Cuban defector, Rafael del Pino Diaz, has
said that Cuba has suffered about 10,000 casualties since 1975.
   Cuban troops were initially sent to Angola that year to protect
the country's Marxist government against attacks from South Africa.
   Recently, South African forces have been assisting the
U.S.-backed UNITA rebel group in Angola. This is one of the issues
delegates from the four countries will discuss at this week's
meetings in London.
   Angola is eager for an end to the South African presence as well
as a suspension of U.S. aid to UNITA.
   The highest priority for the United States and South Africa is
an agreement for the early withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola.
   South Africa has said that once that hurdle is cleared, it will
implement a United Nations resolution calling for independence and
black majority rule in Namibia, Angola's southern neighbor which
has been ruled by Pretoria since early in the century.
   However, there has been no agreement on a timetable for the
mutual withdrawal of foreign forces from both Angola and Namibia.
   The head of the American delegation at Geneva will be Assistant
Secretary of State Chester Crocker, who has been attempting since
1981 to negotiate both Namibian independence and a Cuban troop
withdrawal from Angola.
</TEXT>
