<DOCNO> AP880430-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Labor     04-30 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Labor,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Seamen Fight on Thatcher's Battleground</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of pickets who massed behind
police lines as two strikebreaking ferries sailed into Dover on
Saturday are on the front line in a battle against Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's labor policies.
   Like other unions that mounted major strikes in recent years _
steelworkers, coal miners and newspaper printers _ the seamen
milling on the dockside of this English Channel port say they are
fighting for survival.
   ``You can take our money, but you can't take our minds, you
can't take our hearts,'' said Sam McCluskie, leader of the
24,400-strong National Union of Seamen, whose three-month strike
has crippled P and O European Ferries' cross-channel fleet. ``We
will stand together.''
   The rhetoric has the ring of yesteryear's battles to save jobs
and retain restrictive work practices that critics say slowed
Britain's economic recovery.
   Even as the pickets cheered McCluskie's call for unity, P and
O's strikebreaking ferries, Pride of Bruges and Pride of Kent, were
steaming toward Dover from the Dutch port of Rotterdam.
   Their crews were drawn from the 1,100 P and O ferry workers who
have returned to work on company terms. The pickets are among 720
refusing to go along with P and O's plans to trim its staff and
impose longer working hours. P and O has fired the strikers.
   The company's main rival, Sealink British Ferries, is trying to
keep its fleet in operation by invoking union-curbing legislation
passed since Mrs. Thatcher came to power in 1979.
   Sealink has asked a court to seize the National Union of
Seamen's $5.3 million in assets under a 1984 law barring sympathy
strikes. But the company has moved hesitantly because it does not
want to trigger a nationwide strike.
   Sealink's nervousness and a series of delays by P and O before
the strikebreaking ferries slipped their moorings showed that the
union still has clout.
   Moreover, ships' officers are wary of sailing with non-union
crews, and picket lines discourage potential ferry passengers.
   The Conservative government's law that makes unions liable for
damages over sympathy strikes is the one that helped crack
prolonged and often violent stoppages by newspaper production
unions and coal miners.
   P and O Chairman Sir Jeffrey Sterling says the company must slim
down and relax work practices or be killed by competition from the
Channel Tunnel between England and France, scheduled to open in
1993.
   McCluskie and his strikers also see the battle in apocalyptic
terms.
   ``When I joined the Queen Mary as a cabin boy, I thought I had a
job for life,'' said a 38-year-old seaman who identified himself
only as Arthur for fear of losing his job.
   ``If we lose this,'' he said, ``that's the end of jobs for
British seamen.''
   For the seamen's union, the strike is the bitter fruit of
industrial decline. Britain's once-mighty shipbuilding industry has
collapsed, and many British shipowners have switched to flags of
convenience and hired foreign crews to cut labor costs, as have
shipowners in other industrialized countries.
   Its membership having fallen from 150,000 in the 1950s to below
25,000 today, the National Union of Seamen sees the cross-channel
ferries as its lifeblood.
</TEXT>
