<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     04-30 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Nations Monitoring Group Flies To Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghan-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a U.N. team flew to Kabul
on Saturday to begin preparations for monitoring the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   Maj. General Rauli Helminen of Finland is heading the nine
member U.N. Implementation Assistance Group, which was established
under a memo of understanding signed at Geneva on April 14.
   Pakistan, Afghanistan, the United States and the Soviet Union
signed the memo and an agreement to end nine years of Soviet
military involvement in Afghanistan.
   The group arrived in Pakistan on Monday to discuss its task and
to establish an office in Islamabad, the capital. It will establish
a similar office in Kabul, where it will have talks with Afghan
officials.
   During its stay in Islamabad, the group met with senior
officials of the ministries of Foreign Affairs, Defense, and States
and Frontier Regions.
   ``We have assured the group our fullest cooperation in the
discharge of its functions,'' a Foreign Ministry spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under government rules, said
Pakistan hopes that the group ``will prove useful in bringing about
peace, ensure an orderly withdrawal of the Soviet troops and return
of nearly 5 million Afghan refugees to their homeland from Pakistan
and Iran.''
   Before the departure for Kabul, a spokesman for the U.N. group
said the meetings in Pakistan had been constructive.
   About 115,000 Soviet troops are in Afghanistan, aiding the
communist government in Kabul in its fight against anti-communist
guerrillas.
   Helminen will work as deputy to Diego Cordovez, the U.N. under
secretary- general, who brokered the Geneva peace package.
   The Finnish general will lead a group of about 50 others.
</TEXT>
