<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Prostitution     04-30 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Prostitution,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Launch Search for Human Traffickers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dhaka police have launched a search for
smuggling rings suspected of luring young Bangladeshi women into
foreign prostitution, police sources said Saturday.
   The sources said more than 50 women, most under the age of 30,
were reported missing by their families in the last two months.
Most were believed to have been taken abroad as prostitutes, said
the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Some of the women came to Dhaka for jobs in factories or as
maids, the sources said. Salaries are low, and some of the women
may have sought better-paying work abroad, they said.
   The government is considering introducing legislation that would
provide a death sentence for people convicted of human trafficking.
The current maximum penalty is five years in jail.
</TEXT>
