<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-McDonald's     04-30 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-McDonald's,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Group Calls for McDonald's Boycott</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer action group has
called for a boycott of McDonald's restaurants in West Germany to
protest what it considers the negative effect of fast food on
society and the environment.
   The boycott is being mounted by the Volksmund Information
Bureau, which promotes a variety of local, grass-roots initiatives
in West Germany.
   Oliver Weilandt, a Volksmund spokesman, said Saturday the group
called the boycott because it is concerned about the effects of the
fast-food chain's ``vigorous marketing efforts directed at
children.''
   Weilandt said the group also wants to boycott McDonald's ``to
call attention to a worldwide industrialization of the food
industry that is having catastrophic results on the environment and
on agriculture.''
   Officials of the giant U.S food concern say they plan no action
against the group, but many franchise owners are upset because the
group receives money from the Protestant Church in West Germany.
   ``We are not looking for a fight with the church at all,''
McDonald's marketing supervisor Rolf Kreiner was quoted by the
Protestant Press Service as saying.
   Earlier this month, several McDonald's franchise owners
threatened to stop paying church taxes because of the Protestant
Church's support for Volksmund.
   Kreiner said McDonald's understood the anger of some of its
franchise owners but would not undertake any action against the
church, according to the Protestant Press Service report, which
appeared in the Frankfurt Rundschau daily on Friday.
   The Volksmund group says fast food is unhealthy and that it
worsens local litter problems. The group also charges that
McDonald's forces employees to work part-time to avoid paying them
benefits.
   ``We are targeting McDonald's because it has perfected these
worldwide strategies,'' Weilandt said.
   Officials at the Duesseldorf-based headquarters for McDonald's
in West Germany could not be reached for comment Saturday.
   There are about 262 McDonald's restaurants in West Germany.
</TEXT>
