<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BlackArchbishop Bjt   04-30 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Archbishop, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marino Returns To The South As First Black American Archbishop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bishop Eugene A. Marino, about to become the
first black archbishop of the Roman Catholic Church in America,
returns this week to a South he believes has ``come of age'' since
he left his native Mississippi 36 years ago bearing childhood
wounds of racial prejudice.
   The 53-year-old Marino, an auxiliary bishop in the Washington,
D.C., archdiocese since 1974, will be installed Thursday as
archbishop of Atlanta, taking charge of a 69-county region of
northern Georgia.
   Marino recalls a childhood in Biloxi, Miss., in which, for
example, he and his sister were kicked out of a coin-operated
laundry because they were black. But he said in a recent interview
feels ``personally very comfortable'' about returning to the South.
   ``I think that the South has changed and come of age and
grown,'' he said. ``In many ways, the race question has been more
effectively addressed in much of the South than it has been in the
North.
   ``I think I will be able as a black person to function better in
a Southern situation, as a Southerner, than I might be able to
function in some Northern situation,'' he said.
   Marino's appointment by Pope John Paul II in March came more
than two years after he and other black bishops wrote a pastoral
letter calling on the church to increase the number of blacks in
official positions.
   One of only 12 black bishops in the United States, Marino became
the first to hold an office in the National Conference of Catholic
Bishops when he was elected secretary of the organization in 1985.
   But despite his role as a trailblazer for blacks in the U.S.
Catholic church, and despite Atlanta's long tradition in the civil
rights movement, Marino said he does not necessarily see himself
becoming a leader in that struggle.
   ``I certainly am open to any position that presents itself to
me,'' he said. ``But I don't think leaders go out and become
leaders. I think the situation and the need on one hand, and
opportunities and character and ability on the other, come together
and that's what produces a leader.''
   Still, Marino said he's ``delighted and honored and thrilled''
to be moving to a city ``with a magnificant legacy and such a
beautiful tradition of leadership in this movement.''
   Marino will succeed Archbishop Thomas A. Donnellan, who died
Oct. 15. He said he plans to spend his first year traveling around
the 21,445 square miles of the Atlanta archdiocese, which has a
Catholic population of 156,000 out of a total population of 3.7
million.
   Marino said Catholics in the Atlanta archdiocese should not
expect ``anything tremendously new or different'' under his
leadership. He said his most immediate goal will be to identify the
poor in the area and ``call the people of the church to a greater
awareness of the presence of the poor.''
   As the sixth of eight children growing up in a traditional
Catholic family, Marino attended elementary and high school at Our
Mother of Sorrows Parish in Biloxi and decided at an early age to
become a priest.
   In 1952, at age 18, he entered the Josephites, an order founded
in 1893 to minister to blacks. After four years at St. Joseph's
Minor Seminary in Newburgh, N.Y., he completed his studies for the
priesthood at St. Joseph's Seminary in Washington, D.C., and was
ordained a priest in 1962.
   He taught science and religion at the minor seminary in
Newburgh, then received his Master of Arts degree in religious
education from Fordham University in 1967. He was named spiritual
director of St. Joseph's Seminary in Washington in 1968 and three
years later was elected vicar general of the Josephites.
   During his 14 years as an auxiliary biship in Washington, Marino
was known as an advocate for the poor, the imprisoned and the
homeless, frequently serving as their spokesmen before Congress and
the Washington City Council.
   ``I think that one of the principal demands that Jesus places on
the church and upon those who are the ministers of the churches is
to reach out to the poor and the homeless, to those who are without
shelter,'' he said.
   Marino said he also intends to bring the message that ``we must
be a welcoming church, we must be an evangelizing church,''
particularly to blacks who make up less than 3 percent of the
American Catholic Church.
   ``We are not looking to draw people away from their own
churches,'' he said, ``but we certainly want to invite people who
have no religious affiliation to come and see what it is that we
have.''
</TEXT>
