<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--ArtSeized     04-30 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Art Seized,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Seizes Art, Says Transport Not Authorized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHUNE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs officials seized a truckload of
27 works of art worth $440,000, including paintings by Van Gogh, at
a highway rest stop, officials said Saturday.
   The drawings, watercolors and oil paintings were being
transported through France without proper authorization from London
to Lugano, Switzerland, in an Italian moving van, customs officials
said.
   They said the art was seized after a routine police check April
7 at a rest area near Bethune, about 130 miles north of Paris.
   Police said the works apparently were bought recently at
auctions in London. They include the Vincent Van Gogh oil painting
``Small Farm,'' appraised at $155,000, and two works by Maurice
Utrillo.
   Authorities refused to identify the owner. They said an
investigation was under way to determine why they were being
transported without the necessary documentation. The truck driver
was not charged.
</TEXT>
