<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Taiwan     04-30 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Taiwan,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says Taiwanese Warships Fired on Chinese Fishing Boats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwanese warships fired at two Chinese fishing
vessels trading illegally with Taiwanese in separate incidents, an
official report from China said. Five fishermen were reported
injured.
   The China News Service said in a report appearing in Hong Kong
on Saturday that a fishing boat from Pingtan County in coastal
Fujian province was chased by three navy ships near Taiwan's
northern port of Keelung on April 16.
   The warships fired from about 200 yards away, and three Chinese
fishermen were injured, the report said.
   Two other fishermen were injured April 17 when their Fujian
vessel was fired upon after trading with Taiwanese, the report said.
   All five fishermen were hospitalized in Fujian, it said. It did
not mention damage to the fishing boats.
   Taiwan's Nationalist government fled to the island in 1949 after
losing a civil war to the communists on the mainland. It has
refused all official contact with the Beijing government.
   Direct business ties are forbidden, but Chinese and Taiwanese
fishermen reportedly have a thriving trade in the Taiwan Straits
separating the mainland from the island.
   In Taipei, military and government officials were not
immediately available for comment during the weekend holiday.
   But the Defense Ministry has warned repeatedly that Taiwanese
warships would fire at mainland Chinese fishing boats if they
ignore warnings not to approach Taiwan's coast to trade with local
fishermen.
   Officials have said the military has intensified coastal patrols
in recent months because Chinese fishing boats have ``harassed''
local fishing boats since Taiwan lifted martial law last July.
</TEXT>
