<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Quake     04-30 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Quake,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Earthquake Shakes Area South Of Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake shook the hills near the pope's
summer residence south of Rome on Saturday and was felt in the
capital, but there were no reports of injury or damage.
   The National Institute of Geophysics said the quake measured
between 4 and 5 on the Mercalli scale and that the epicenter was in
the Castelli Romani region, a group of hill towns about 16 miles
south of Rome.
   Castel Gandolfo, the summer residence of the pope, is in the
area.
   The Department of Civil Protection said there were no reports of
injury or damage.
   The Mercalli scale gauges the intensity of an earthquake as felt
in a specific location. The scale runs from 1 to 12. A reading of 1
means the quake is only felt by a few people, and a reading of 12
indicates a major quake.
</TEXT>
