<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-30 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Clark finished last in all nine triathlons he
entered last year, but he says he was the winner. Just living is a
victory for the 49-year-old heart-transplant recipient.
   ``I used to live for the bonus check at the end of each month,''
said the former Tuscon, Ariz., insurance executive who will compete
here Sunday in a triathlon. ``Now, the way I look at it, every day
is a bonus check.
   ``I'm not out there to win any race. But I feel that every race
I'm in I win,'' he said.
   As a successful executive, Clark worked 16 hours a day, smoked
heavily and never exercised. But that changed when he received a
heart transplant in 1985 after a yearlong bout with heart disease.
   He started walking, and four months later entered a
five-kilometer walkathon. Six weeks after that, he entered a
10-kilometer race, walking much of the way and finishing dead last.
   Triathlons _ races that combine running, swimming and bicycling
_ were his next step. He started training and in April 1986 entered
one in Tuscon.
   ``People were saying, `Hurry up, hurry up!' and I was like `I'm
moving. That's fast enough.' I was like the clown in the rodeo,''
Clark said.
   As he trained for the Sunday event, he recalled a race in
Phoenix last year. While awaiting the start, he spotted Herschel
and Brenda Tweed, parents of the teen-ager whose heart he received.
   ``I walked over and they all gave me a hug,'' said Clark. ``Then
just before the race they were yelling, `Go get 'em, Gary!' I was
actually crying, standing there before the start of the race.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of stickup artists had it all figured out
_ guns, masks, the armored car stopped at a currency exchange. They
just got ahead of themselves, police said.
   Shortly after noon Friday, an armored car pulled up to the
Northwest Side Currency Exchange. The guard got out, walking toward
the building.
   Just then, a gun-toting, masked robber stepped out of a
passageway.
   Robber: ``This is a stickup!''
   Guard: ``I don't have any money yet. This is a pickup.''
   Felonious frustration!
   The gunman pointed his gun in the air and fired once, then took
off running with an accomplice who had been waiting nearby.
   ``It was well planned and thought out,'' said police Sgt.
William Murray. ``But they got it backwards.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hundred photographers who fanned out
throughout California were attempting to capture the essence of the
Golden State in a single day.
   ``It was a fascinating idea, and still is, to capture a country
or a state in a day,'' said Seny Norasingh, one of the
photographers for the book ``A Day in the Life of California.''
   Norasingh was one of 100 photographers who took part in ther
project Friday. The book, set to be published this fall, will be
the eighth in a series of books of pictures taken in a certain
place in a single day.
   Norasingh spent his day in San Francisco's Chinatown, where
inside a Roman Catholic school surrounded by shops and restaurants,
children began with the pledge of allegiance, a prayer and a song.
   ``Almost all my pictures in the other books were something I
shot on my own,'' said Norasingh, who also worked on the books on a
day in the life in Spain, America and the Soviet Union.
