<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Spain-Drugs     04-30 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Spain-Drugs,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest More Than 1,000 in Spanish Drug Raids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested more than 1,000 people
and seized hundreds of weapons in a 48-hour nationwide crackdown on
small-time drug pushers and criminals, police said Saturday.
   It was the fourth such police operation since early last year,
when the government of Socialist Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez
decided to stiffen penalties for drug dealers and try to eliminate
drug-peddling areas in the country's major cities.
   Spain has become a major point of entry into Europe for Latin
American cocaine and Middle Eastern and southeast Asian heroin,
international drug enforcement officials say.
   Authorities said they arrested 1,038 suspects in the raids and
seized three pounds each of heroin and cocaine, 275 pounds of
hashish and 1,500 pills of hallucinogenic drugs.
   Officers also confiscated 35 guns, 479 knives and nearly
$270,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
