<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Homosexuality     04-30 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Homosexuality,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>15,000 Protest British Homosexuality Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 15,000 gay rights supporters marched
Saturday to protest a new anti-homosexuality law that they say will
allow censorship of the arts.
   The demonstrators gathered from all over the country and
streamed through central London to a rally against the government
bill, which becomes law on June 1.
   Actress Maria Aitken said she supported the protest because she
is worried that the law will result in censorship of works by
homosexuals.
   The government measure is a blanket stipulation stating that
local authorities must not ``intentionally promote homosexuality.''
   The government has accused some left-wing local authorities of
using state funds to promote homosexuality as an acceptable
lifestyle.
   Opponents say wording of the measure is so broad that it can be
used to censor artistic works, particularly books and plays by or
about homosexuals.
   Several members of the Royal Shakespeare Company joined
Saturday's march. A British legislator and two Italian lawmakers
also took part in the protest.
   One demonstrator, actor Michael Cashman, is widely known for his
role as Colin, a gay man in the British Broadcasting Corp.'s soap
opera ``EastEnders,'' broadcast in the United States.
   ``The importance of this protest is to show that we are
determined to stand up and fight for our rights as human beings,''
he said.
   In New York City, about a hundred sympathizers demonstrated in
midtown Manhattan, carrying placards in support of the British
homosexual cause.
</TEXT>
