<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-US 1stLd-Writethru a0541 04-30 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0541,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Shippers Warily Welcome U.S. Move To Expand Protection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 12-17, bgng `In the ...,' with 10 grafs to UPDATE
with Iranian response and convoy report. PICKS up 18th graf pvs,
`U.S., British, ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision to widen the U.S. military
role in the Persian Gulf could make the United States the policeman
of the waterway, despite its aversion to the task, gulf shipping
officials said Saturday.
   The shipping community generally welcomed President Reagan's
decision to expand its protection of foreign vessels from attacks
by Iran. But some shippers also complained that the new policy does
not go far enough.
   ``The best attitude to adopt now is a wait-and-see one,'' said a
shipping executive who has complained that his vessels, mainly
flying Asian flags, were left at the mercy of Iran as the big
powers protected their own shipping.
   ``From what has been annnounced, protection has not been
guaranteed for all ships,'' he said. ``It sounds like an elastic
policy that will be used by the United States at the right moment,
when they choose to take on the Iranians.''
   Under the policy announced Friday, U.S. forces will go to the
aid of non-communist, neutral ships that ask for help after being
fired upon.
   Previously, U.S. warships protected only those ships reflagged
with U.S. flags or registered as U.S.-flagged vessels, including 11
Kuwaiti oil tankers.
   The Navy escorts through the gulf, however, frequently have
picked up ``hitchhiker'' vessels that are not U.S. flagged.
   ``In effect, (the new policy) could turn out to be a substitute
for the proposal to have a U.N. naval task force protect shipping
in the gulf until the Iraq-Iran war ends,'' said another gulf
shipping executive.
   ``And despite statements by U.S. officials, the United States is
going to find itself becoming the policeman in the waterway.''
   He was referring to U.S. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci's
comment that despite the policy change, the United States was not
the ``policemen of the gulf, nor do we wish to be.''
   Said another executive: ``I think the Americans are taking on a
tremendous load ... doing the job the United Nations is supposed to
do.''
   Iran's state-run radio said Saturday that Washington's decision
proved the United States was backing Iraq in the 7{-year-old war.
   The radio said that by protecting neutral vessels, the United
States will be ``seeking to limit the Islamic Republic of Iran's
retaliatory powers.''
   Iran attacks neutral vessels in retaliation for Iraqi strikes on
Iranian oil installations and tankers.
   In the past year, 46 Americans have been killed in or near the
gulf, including two U.S. Marine pilots who disappeared with their
aircraft April 18 after reporting hostile radar locked on their
helicopter. Iran claimed the aircraft was shot down.
   The biggest loss of American life occurred May 17 in an
accidental Iraqi missile strike on the frigate Stark. Thirty-seven
U.S. sailors died.
   The Soviet Union has sought a multinational naval escort force
in the gulf under the U.N. flag. Less than 10 percent of the ships
sailing gulf waters fly communist-bloc flags
   The gulf supplies nearly 20 percent of the non-communist world's
petroleum and is the major trading route for the coastal states
that depend on imports for most of their food and commodity
supplies.
   The spread of hostilities into the gulf from the Iraq-Iran war
has harmed port trade and tended to reduce ship traffic in the
waterway.
   Still, an average of 20 tankers and freighters a day make their
way in and out of the Strait of Hormuz, the entry to the gulf.
   On Saturday, the 27th convoy this year of reflagged Kuwaiti
ships headed out of the gulf escorted by U.S. Navy warships, a U.S.
military spokesman said.
   U.S., British, French, Italian and Soviet warships escorting
their commercial vessels became routine last year when the Iranians
stepped up their attacks on commercial shipping with gunboat
attacks and the laying of mines.
   None of the shipping executives who commented on the U.S. policy
change would be quoted by name. Many of the officials do business
with both Iraq and Iran.
   Some shipping executives said they believed Iran would find ways
to continue menacing ships despite the expanded U.S. Navy role.
   ``Who's to prevent the Iranians sowing hundreds of mines in the
waterway? They manufacture them,'' said one. ``Who's to prevent
them firing Silkworm anti-ship missiles at a convoy moving through
the Hormuz?
   ``They will be ready to take in stride the U.S. Navy taking on
all their missile batteries there. In the end, it's the United
States that will be the loser, finding itself in a state of war.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
