<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Rebels     04-30 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Rebels,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maoist Rebels Hang Three Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas hanged three peasant
women in the highlands after accusing them of washing soldiers'
clothes and selling food to the soldiers, police said Saturday.
   Elsewhere, an armed cadre of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement, a pro-Cuba rebel group, seized a Lima bus late Friday on
a downtown street, ordered passengers off, exploded firebombs and
burned the bus, police said.
   A column of Shining Path guerrillas dragged the three peasant
women from their home in an isolated farming settlement before dawn
Friday and strung them up on a nearby tree, police said.
   ``We hanged them like dogs for collaborating with dogs,''
witnesses quoted one of the guerrillas as saying.
   The women, aged 60, 50 and 25, lived together in Ruguyoc, 35
miles north of the state capital, Ayacucho, which is 235 miles
southeast of Lima.
   The fanatical Shining Path frequently has shot or stabbed to
death peasants in reprisal for aid the campesinos provide to the
military.
   The government says more than 10,000 people, mainly highland
peasants, have been killed during the Shining Path's eight-year
insurgency to install a worker-peasant state.
   The Tupac Amaru group has been active, mainly in Lima, since
1984. The group is smaller and considered much less violent that
the Shining Path.
</TEXT>
