<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Afghanistan     04-30 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Afghanistan,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib To Visit India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib of Afghanistan will
visit India early next month for talks with the Indian government,
Kabul radio reported Saturday.
   The radio broadcast monitored in New Delhi said the visit likely
would take place in the first week of May. Najib will lead a
high-level delegation to New Delhi for official talks, the
state-run radio said.
   Indian officials contacted by telephone could not immediately
confirm the report.
   India, which has close ties to the Soviet Union, invited Najib
for talks last week. The invitation came from Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi.
   An estimated 115,000 Soviet troops are to begin pulling out of
Afghanistan on May 15 under an accord signed in Geneva on April 14.
The troops entered the landlocked nation in December 1979 to prop
up the communist government.
   India did not condemn the Soviet presence in Afghanistan and
officially maintained that the troops came on the invitation of the
Afghan government.
   Gandhi has been seeking to take part in the latest developments
in Afghanistan. He invited President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq of
Pakistan for talks on the Afghan situation, but Zia declined the
invitation.
   Pakistan has been home for thousands of Afghan refugees and
rebels who left their country because of the conflict.
</TEXT>
