<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NewCaledonia 1stLd-Writethru   04-30 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0547,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Forces Trade Fire With Separatist Guerrillas
^Eds: Inserts one graf after 13th, ``Two of...'' to note that
government considers released hostages to still be hostages; picks
up 14th pvs: The native...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French patrol boat opened fire on
Melanesian separatists Saturday in the navy's first direct role in
violence that has left seven people dead on this island territory.
   Twenty-one French police officers were still held hostage in
caves on the New Caledonian island of Ouvea. An opposition
spokesman demanded that France agree to a referendum on
independence.
   In Paris, the main separatist movement accused the French
government of waging a ``colonial war'' against the native
Melanesians.
   About 25 military policemen traded gunfire with about 30 armed
rebels near a guerrilla encampment at Pouebo, a village on the
island's east coast, said Philippe Berges, chief of staff at the
French High Commission office here.
   A patrol boat just off the coast fired submachine guns at the
insurgents, he said. No injuries were reported on either side.
   But the exchange was indicative of the rapidly escalating
proportions of the conflict. Asked if the insurgency had reached
civil war stage, Berges said: ``It's beginning to look that way.''
   The main separatist group, the Kanak Socialist National
Liberation Front, said in a statement in Paris that the navy
detroyed a fishermen's cooperative in Pouebo. It charged that the
French army was stepping up its operations throughout the territory.
   ``Faced with this situation of colonial war, the Kanak people
are organizing to thwart the occupation forces,'' the statement
said.
   Front spokesman Leopold Joredie said Saturday that the group
wants a mediator appointed to negotiate terms of an island-wide
referendum on self-rule.
   He said a mediator must be named before the insurgents will
respond to President Francois Mitterrand's appeal for the immediate
release of the hostages.
   The violence began April 22 when separatists tried to block
French presidential elections scheduled on New Caledonia on April
24. Rebels raided a police station, kidnapping 27 gendarmes and
killing four others.
   Twelve hostages were subsequently released. But eight more
lawmen were seized Wednesday when they tried to negotiate the
release of the remaining hostages.
   Two of those hostages, the head of an anti-terrorism squad and
an assistant prosecutor, were subsequently released and ordered to
negotiate on behalf of the terrorists. They were told the remaining
hostages would be killed if the two men did not return to the rebel
hideout.
   Because of that threat, the government said it considers the two
to still be hostages.
   The native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, make up 43 percent of
the territory's 145,000 people. About 36 percent of the population
is European, with the rest primarily Asian or Tahitian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
