<DOCNO> AP880430-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Khrushchev     04-30 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Khrushchev,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khrushchev Paved Way For Glasnost, Son Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAGREB, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nikita Khrushchev laid the groundwork
for glasnost more than three decades ago, the son of the late
Soviet leader was quoted Saturday as saying.
   The democratic-style reforms of Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev are similar to changes unsuccessfully sought by
Khrushchev, Sergei Khrushchev was quoted as saying in an interview
with the Yugoslav daily Vjesnik.
   ``I hope Mikhail Gorbachev succeeds where my father did not,
because there is no alternative to changes and perestroika,'' he
said. Perestroika, or reconstruction, and glasnost, or openess, are
buzzwords for Gorbachev's reforms.
   ``My father was the first to `shake' the Soviet bureaucratic
society. He dared to unmask (Soviet dictator Joseph) Stalin, start
economic reforms and democratization and urge a dialogue with the
United States on curbing the arms race,'' Sergei Khrushchev was
quoted as saying.
   ``If my father had not begun then, 33 years ago, it would be
more difficult for Gorbachev now.''
   Excerpts of what was described as Sergei Khrushchev's first
interview with a foreign journalist were carried by the state news
agency Tanjug. Tanjug did not say when or where the interview was
given or disclose personal details about the younger Khrushchev.
   His comments came just a few days after a Soviet newspaper,
Moscow News, made similar observations.
   The report also came as Soviet scholars and writers are trying
to come to grips with Stalin's legacy. During Stalin's almost three
decades of rule, millions of Soviets died as a result of purges and
crash programs of industrialization and collectivization of
agriculture.
   Khrushchev consolidated his power after Stalin died in 1953 but
was forced out in 1964 by Communist Party leaders, including his
ultimate successor, Leonid Brezhnev.
   Sergei Khrushchev charged that Brezhnev's treatment of his
father was ``inhuman.''
   ``My father always behaved correctly toward Brezhnev. He brought
him to the Kremlin, but Brezhnev (leaned) toward those who
conspired against Khrushchev.''
   Sergei Khrushchev said his father was competely isolated after
removal from power and when he died, the Communist Party daily
Pravda mentioned it in a three-line announcement.
   He said he was working on the publication of his father's
memoirs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
