<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PromRevival     04-30 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prom Revival,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Townspeople Enjoy Spectacle of First Prom Since 1962</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM PARSONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORREST CITY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gawkers began gathering more than
an hour before the 9 p.m. start of the first Forrest City High
School Senior Prom in more than a quarter-century.
   They sat in pickup trucks and cars in the parking lot of the
Civic Center; others cruised the lot, eyeing the front door. Some
may have been drawn by the mobile van of a Little Rock television
station, its satellite transmission dish aimed skyward.
   Mostly, they were curious.
   It was the first integrated Senior Prom for the school. The last
Senior Prom was held in 1962 and blacks did not begin attending
Forrest City High until 1965.
   A group of black junior high youngsters gathered near the
entrance, waiting to see what their older friends and relatives
looked like in their tuxedos and formals _ some bought, some made
and some rented.
   ``We'll be going to the Junior Prom'' in May, said Ora Jamerson,
14, from amid a group of four young girls. In the meantime, she was
enjoying the spectacle, calling out to her older friends, waving,
admiring their togs.
   Janet Hamm, 18, among the older, white onlookers, wasn't dressed
for the prom. She dropped out of school in January.
   ``I don't think it'll work out,'' she said. ``There's a lot of
racial problems in Forrest City. I just don't think it'll work
out.''
   But police, who were on hand to enforce the school
administration's strict no-cigarettes, no-alcohol, no-drug policy,
said the celebration proceeded without incident.
   ``Everything stayed quiet,'' Police Sgt. Willie Gibbs said at 2
a.m. Saturday.
   Outside the Civic Center, as the prom got under way, there were
a few good-natured jeers at unfamiliar finery _ no catcalls or
taunts, racial or otherwise.
   Tangella Brown, 17, Student Council president, said just having
it all finally come together, after months of planning, was perhaps
the most important thing for her. The final day's preparations and
decorations took so long that she was 45 minutes late herself.
   Earlier in the week, she said the prom owed its existence to the
enthusiasm of her classmates, who number about 350.
   ``Each class has their own thoughts about things, each class
thinks they're better,'' she said. ``We felt like we would have a
prom, and we did.''
</TEXT>
