<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Ferries 1stLd-Writethru   04-30 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ferries, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0544,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pickets Attack Passenger Buses; Strikebreaking Ferries Dock</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after graf 7 `Police quickly...control
them.'' to UPDATE with strike affecting other areas, PICK UP graf 9
pvs `Strikebound P...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking ferry workers pelted busloads of
tourists with rocks and bottles Saturday after mistaking them for
strikebreakers, police said. Later, two ferries docked at Dover as
the company moved to crush the work stoppage.
   Trouble flared early Saturday when five buses carrying ferry
passengers drove to the dock behind a police cruiser with flashing
lights. Hundreds of pickets, mistaking the tourists for
strikebreaking crews, surged through police lines, threw rocks and
bottles at the buses and hammered on the windows, police said.
   About 150 officers moved in and quickly broke up the dsturbances
after scuffles with pickets.
   Dover police Inspector Mervyn Williams said a bus windshield was
smashed but no one was hurt. One striker was arrested but was later
released without charge.
   Police Superintendent Tim O'Connor said the buses were carrying
passengers into the ferry terminal for crossings on French and
Belgian ships to Calais and Ostend.
   ``Some of them were schoolchildren,'' O'Connor said. ``They were
terrified.''
   Police quickly restored order, but Sam McCluskie, leader of the
24,400-member National Union of Seamen, said: ``I cannot guarantee
it will be peaceful for long. I want peace, but these men and women
have been frustrated to the extent I will not be able to control
them.''
   The P and O strike and support by other seamen also affected
crossings from England and Wales to Ireland and the Isle of Man,
and between Scotland and Northern Ireland and the Shetland and
Orkney islands.
   Later Saturday, two ferries sailed into Dover without incident
after crossing the English Channel.
   Strikebound P and O European Ferries Ltd. said the Pride of
Bruges and the Pride of Kent picked up replacement crews and sailed
from Rotterdam in the Netherlands to Dover, one of the world's
busiest ports.
   P and O said the two ferries would begin crossing the English
Channel on a regular basis.
   McCluskie said British crews on the P and O ferries ``will be
marked as scabs forever.''
   The company refused to say when the ferries would try to load
passengers and freight and set sail for France. The captain of the
Pride of Kent, however, told Dover Harbor Board in a ship-to-shore
radio message: ``We will be laid here for 24 hours _ at least that
is Plan A.'' Details of the plan were not made known.
   ``The ships are in port while provisioning is completed and it
is made ready to take passengers,'' said P and O director Graeme
Dunlop.
   P and O workers are striking to protest the company's plan to
cut jobs, lengthen shifts and change work rules to have employees
perform more tasks. The company says its must trim its staff so it
can compete with the English Channel tunnel connecting England and
France, which is set to open in 1992.
   About 750 pickets gathered on the dockside during the night to
protest the arrival of the two P and O ferries from Rotterdam.
   The ferries, carrying 250 crew members but no passengers,
anchored overnight in the Solent and then sailed into port and
berthed Saturday morning.
   P and O and its main rival, Sealink British Ferries, hit by a
sympathy strike, warned of long delays at Dover for any vacationers
heading for continental Europe during the three-day British holiday
weekend.
   The Pride of Kent and the Pride of Bruges were among five of P
and O's 17 vessels that had been moored in Rotterdam since the
strike began Feb. 4.
   They were crewed by 250 of the 1,100 P and O seamen who have
accepted the company's new terms. P and O this week fired 720
workers still on strike.
</TEXT>
