<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Senegal-Trial     04-30 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senegal-Trial,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys For Opposition Leader Quit, Claim Violation Of Defense
Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for opposition leader Abdoulaye
Wade said Saturday they will no longer participate in Wade's trial
becaus of a judge's ruling.
   On Friday, the 40 European and African lawyers defending Wade
left the courtroom to protest the judge's refusal to let them
question a policeman who led the investigation into Wade's
activities.
   In a statement released Saturday, the lawyers announced their
decision to discontinue their defense of Wade, citing what they
said was a a violation by the court of the rights of the defense.
   Wade, also a lawyer, is charged with compromising state security
and inciting violence in the three days of rioting that followed
Feb. 28 presidential and legislative elections. He and seven other
opposition members face up to five years in prison if convicted of
various charges.
   Wade lost the election to President Abdou Diouf, receiving only
25 percent of the votes to Diouf's 73 percent.
   Wade said Diouf's Socialist Party rigged the elections, assuring
the president of a second five-year term and 103 seats in the
120-seat National Assembly.
   But Wade has said he was not responsible for the violence that
occurred when rampaging youths damaged buildings, barricaded
streets and burned cars in the capital after the elections. A
dusk-to-dawn curfew was imposed but it was lifted two weeks ago.
   Judge Ali Cire Ba on Friday adjourned the trial until Tuesday.
He said if the defense refused to participate in the proceedings he
would ask the prosecutor to indict Wade without hearing any further
testimony.
   Wade supporters have twice clashed with riot police outside the
courtroom since the trial opened last week. On Monday they burned
five government vehicles.
</TEXT>
