<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0587 04-30 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0587,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Palestinians and Israeli Soldier Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 13th graf ``Since anti-Israeli...'' to
ADD Palestinian leaflet calling for protests Sunday. Pickup 14th
graf pvs ``Jerusalem Mayor...''</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The military censor ordered significant
deletions from this dispatch.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian youths pelted troops with stones
Saturday in scattered anti-Israeli protests in the occupied
territories, and four Palestinians and a soldier were injured,
military and Arab sources said.
   The occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip were relatively quiet
after one of the calmest weeks since a Palestinian uprising began
December 8. Israeli officials, encouraged by the relative calm,
have claimed that the protests are fading.
   In the main marketplace of Nablus, the largest city in the West
Bank, Palestinian youths attacked Israeli troops with stones,
according to an army representative who spoke on condition of
anonymity. The troops opened fire and wounded a protester, he said.
   Arab reporters in Nablus said a second protester was wounded.
   In the nearby Balata refugee camp, young Palestinians hurled
stones at Israeli troops, injuring one, the spokesman said. Troops
wounded a protester there too, he said.
   The military clamped a curfew on the camp right after the
incident, forcing residents to stay home.
   In the West Bank city of Hebron, a group of Jewish settlers from
the nearby Kiryat Arba settlement were surrounded by stone-throwing
youths, the spokesman said. The settlers fired shots in the air
until troops arrived, he said, and there were no injuries.
   Also Saturday, a Palestinian youth arrived at Hebron's Alia
hospital with a gunshot wound in his arm, a doctor said. The army
confirmed the report but said it was not clear how the youth was
shot.
   In Gaza City, students blocked a main street with flaming tires,
boulders and trash cans, Arab reporters said. They waved outlawed
Palestinian flags and chanted: ``Our lives for Palestine!''
   The students dispersed on army orders, the reporters said.
   Since anti-Israeli violence broke out in the occupied
territories, which Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East War, 175
Palestinians have been slain. One Israeli soldier and one Israeli
civilian have been killed.
   Palestinian activists, in a leaflet circulated late Friday,
urged Arabs to keep the uprising alive and said ``the blood of our
martyrs must not be spilled for nothing.''
   It called for commercial strikes and a ``day of confrontation
with the occupation forces'' on Sunday.
   The leaflet, signed by the ``United Leadership of the
Upsrising,'' also made its most direct call for attacks on
Israeli-appointed Arab mayors who have refused to yield to the
militants' demands that they resign. It singled out the mayors of
the West Bank towns of Hebron, Ramallah, El Bireh and Jericho.
   Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kollek protested a cartoon published in
the Los Angeles Times depicting Jesus being turned away from
Jerusalem by Israeli troops, who told him the city was a closed
military area.
   The cartoon, published March 30, was an apparent reference to
the frequent closures imposed by the military in the occupied
territories in an effort to quell the uprising.
   ``In all its history, Jerusalem has never been freer or more
open to visitors to holy places than it is now,'' Kollek declared
in a telegram to the paper earlier this week, said spokeswoman
Sevannah Meryn on Friday.
   The cartoon was one of two that angered Israel's consul general
in Los Angeles, Eitan Ben Tzur, Israel radio said.
   The second cartoon, published April 27, depicted an Israeli
soldier holding a smoking rifle atop a pile of bullet-ridden
bodies. The caption read: ``I'm willing to talk peace, but there
aren't any Palestinians to talk peace with!''
</TEXT>
