<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FAA-Plane 4thLd-Writethru a0610 04-30 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAA-Plane, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0610,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Issues Restrictions For Older 737s After Hawaii Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 2nd graf bgng: The Federal ... and inserts 2 grafs after
7th graf bgng: Farrar said ... to UPDATE with FAA now saying half
of jets are outside of U.S., Boeing comment. Sub 10th graf bgng: In
Hawaii ... to add Aloha total.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Older Boeing 737s, like the jet that ripped
open over Hawaii last week, were restricted Saturday from flying at
altitudes above 23,000 feet until they can be inspected for
structural defects.
   The Federal Aviation Administration issued an emergency order
for jets in the 737-100 and 737-200 series that have had more than
55,000 flights. The order affects 66 planes, half of them in the
fleets of Aloha, Piedmont and American airlines, FAA spokesman Fred
Farrar said. The rest belong to international carriers.
   Federal investigators are focusing on possible structural
failure in the Aloha Airlines jet that blew open Thursday at 24,000
feet. A flight attendant was swept out of the plane to her death
and 61 passengers were injured.
   Under the airworthiness directive issued by FAA Administrator T.
Allan McArtor, the airlines must complete visual inspections of the
affected area within the next 500 flights.
   ``They must inspect the area for cracking, corrosion or
de-lamination and if any is found, it must be repaired and the
suspect pieces replaced,'' Farrar said.
   The area to be inspected is the top of the fuselage. In the
Aloha jet, a huge upper section of the 737-200 tore away, leaving
passengers exposed to the open skies and forcing the pilot to make
an emergency landing.
   Farrar said that at altitudes of 23,000 feet or below, the
pressure between the outside and inside of the aircraft is such
that a structural weakness would not cause a failure or damage to
the plane.
   Farrar originally said that all 66 affected jets belonged to
U.S. carriers. However, he later said that about half of the jets
belonged to international airlines. He said the FAA did not know
which ones.
   Tom Cole, a Boeing spokesman in Seattle, said Boeing also did
not know which international carriers flew the affected 737s. He
said the company would try to find that out Monday.
   A Piedmont Airlines spokesman, Bill Kress, said from
Winston-Salem, N.C., that the airline had already begun inspecting
the 17 affected 737-200s in its fleet. He said such inspections
were part of the airline's regular maintenance program for the jets
and the order would have ``virtually no effect on our operation.''
   ``The aircraft is such that we use it on short hauls anyhow and
we don't need to attain that altitude of 23,000 feet,'' he said.
   In Hawaii, Aloha spokesman Milton Goto said he hadn't heard of
the FAA order and had no immediate comment. Aloha has three jets
affected by the FAA order, in addition to the one involved in the
accident, according to Boeing.
   American Airlines said 16 of its 737s were affected by the FAA
order, and those are used on short-haul West Coast routes that do
not require flying above 23,000 feet. Spokesman Steve McGregor said
from Dallas that the airline would inspect those planes within 48
hours.
   McGregor called the FAA action ``prudent,'' and said, ``We're
going to comply with it more quickly than required. We're simply
going to do it as quickly as we can.''
   Last October 5, the FAA ordered close inspection of the upper
skin of the early model Boeing 737s because routine inspections had
turned up cracks near where sections of sheet metal overlap. The
agency warned the problem could cause rapid cabin decompression.
   The inspections also found metal strips on the fuselage coming
loose on some early-model Boeing 737s because the lamination was no
longer holding.
   The earlier FAA directive covered the first 291 Boeing 737s
manufactured, of which the Aloha plane was No. 152. It had been in
service since 1969.
   Aloha Airlines has said it conducted the inspections in October
as ordered but found nothing that caused alarm.
   Boeing spokesman Jim Boynton said Friday in Seattle the company
has issued service bulletins on the need for periodic inspections
for possible cracking or structural weakening because of corrosion
of the skin of the older Boeing 737s.
   Boynton said the company's most recent bulletin had been issued
two weeks before Thursday's incident.
   Farrar said Saturday's directive was broader than the one issued
in October because the new directive orders visual inspections of
the entire top of the fuselage. He said the order will probably
mean an increase in fuel costs for the airlines because the higher
a jet flies, te more fuel-efficient it is.
   National Transportation Safety Board member Joseph T. Nall said
Friday that investigators believed the cause of the Aloha accident
was a structural problem with the Aloha jet.
   He also said the jet had been through 85,000 to 90,000
takeoff-and-landing cycles, and called that ``a high cycle number''
because of the stress caused by repeated expansions and
contractions of the fuselage.
   Earlier, Boeing asked for inspection of all Boeing 737-200 jets
that have completed more than 55,000 takeoff and landing cycles.
Meanwhile, Aloha grounded three jets similar in age to the one
involved in Thursday's accident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
