<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SoCalQuakes     04-30 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SoCal Quakes,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Small Quakes Shake Southern California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to restore AP logo</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two small earthquakes rattled Southern
California Saturday, one an aftershock of the destructive Oct. 1
Whittier Narrows temblor and the other near the Mexican border,
authorities said.
   The aftershock measuring 3.2 on the Richter scale hit at 11:40
a.m., said Robert Finn, spokesman for the California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena.
   Its epicenter was placed four miles southeast of Pasadena on the
fault that produced the October quake, which caused millions of
dollars in damage.
   A quake measuring 3.0 on the Richter scale hit just before 9
a.m. about 12 miles southeast of downtown San Diego, Finn said.
   No injuries or damage were reported in either quake, sheriff's
deputies said.
   Quakes with a Richter reading of less than 3.5 can cause slight
damage in a local area.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
</TEXT>
