<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Socialists     04-30 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Socialists,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latin American Socialists Criticize U.S. Sanctions Against Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Socialist International
committee on Saturday criticized U.S. efforts to oust Panama's
strongman Gen. Manuel Noriega, saying only the Panamanian people
are suffering.
   The Reagan administration's economic sanctions against Panama
``not only violate the non-intervention principle, but also are
only causing suffering to the Panamanian people,'' the Socialist
International Commitee for Latin America and the Caribbean said in
a declaration.
   The committee said the only solution for Panama's crisis should
be negotiations between the government and the opposition ``to
guarantee free elections, a definitive role for the Defense Forces
and independence for the civilian power.''
   Noriega is commander of the 15,000-member Defense Forces and
controls the civilian government.
   The declaration was approved after a two-day meeting in Rio of
Socialist International delegates from 20 organizations in Latin
America and the Caribbean. Observers from the United States and
Europe also attended.
   The main topics on the agenda included the advancement and
strengthening of democracy in South America, the peace process in
Central America and the future of democracy and development in the
Caribbean.
   A report with the committee's conclusions will be presented to
the Socialist International World Council meeting to be held May
11-12 in Madrid, Spain.
</TEXT>
