<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0603 04-30 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0603,0837</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Strike Settled, Second Continues At Steel Mill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf ``In the...'' to UPDATE with
police patrolling Krakow and Warsaw.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikers occupying a machinery plant in
southeast Poland ended their sit-in Saturday after apparently
winning promises of higher pay, but a walkout by thousands of steel
workers persisted with no end in sight.
   The developments came as the Polish government prepared for its
big May Day celebrations. Solidarity, the banned trade union
federation, called for nationwide protests to mark the nation's
biggest official holiday.
   In the history of the communist government, there has never been
a large-scale strike in progress on May Day.
   Strike leaders said dozens of police vans and vehicles including
water cannons moved into positions near the Lenin steel mill in
Nowa Huta late Saturday. There were also large numbers of police in
other parts of Krakow and in Warsaw in an apparent show of strength
before May Day.
   More than 40 opposition activists were rounded up by police to
prevent them from taking part in the holiday protests, said
Zbigniew Romaszewski, a Warsaw Solidarity spokesman.
   One of Poland's senior anti-government activists, Kornel
Morawiecki, founder of the splinter dissident group Fighting
Solidarity, was freed from prison nearly six months after his
arrest through apparent negotiations by the country's powerful
Roman Catholic church.
   Morawiecki was freed with Andrzej Kolodziej, another member of
Fighting Solidarity.
   The two men were flown to Rome after initially refusing to leave.
   A strike by what organizers said was about 15,000 workers at the
Lenin steel mill in Nowa Huta outside Krakow entered its fifth day
with no sign of a breakthrough.
   The 7,000 striking workers occupying a heavy machinery plant at
Stalowa Wola, about 150 miles southeast of Warsaw, left the factory
Saturday at about 2 p.m. after management agreed to their pay
demands, said Grzegorz Surdy, a spokesman for the strikers.
   The Rev. Jan Niemiec, a Roman Catholic priest in Stalowa Wola,
said the strikers received nothing in writing but that their
demands were expected to be met.
   The state-run news agency PAP also reported the one-day strike
ended but denied there were any negotiations with the strikers.
   ``In view of the illegal character of the protest action, no
negotiations had been held with the striking group,'' the report
said.
   The labor crisis began Monday and is the most serious to
confront Poland since the December 1981 declaration of martial law
and the banning of Solidarity.
   In a positive development for the government, Krakow's tram
drivers ignored a Solidarity call for a strike Saturday.
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski was to address the nation
during the May Day celebration in the capital of Warsaw, which was
festooned with banners, red party flags and red-and-white national
colors in the country's biggest official holiday.
   The holiday is dedicated to working people and in recent years
has been an occasion for sometimes violent protests for Solidarity.
   Surdy, a student and twice-jailed Solidarity activist, said
Saturday he was surprised that authorities had not attempted to
stop the Nowa Huta strike before the holiday.
   In a communique issued through the Polish news agency
Interpress, the plant management said that as of Saturday, it would
begin docking strikers' pay and would close down restaurants and
snack bars on the plant grounds.
   In an apparent hardening of the positions of strikers, three
fired Solidarity activists _ including Mieczyslaw Gil, the former
head of the Solidarity at the plant _ were named to the strike
committee.
   One of the committee's demands is that the three be rehired.
   Unlike Poland's last wave of labor unrest in 1980-81, which gave
rise to Solidarity, the workers did not cover the plant with
banners or mix political and economic demands.
   Photographs taken in work areas inside the plant showed workers
reading newsapers, sleeping or talking on the telephone.
   After four days of the strike ``there is weariness and already a
little boredom,'' Surdy said, but he emphasized that workers
intended to stay off the jobs ``until our demands are met.''
   Besides the reinstatement of the fired workers, the steel
workers are demanding an immediate 50 percent raise on the average
salary of $105 a month.
   At Stalowa Wola, where the occupation strike began Friday, the
demands included a $50 monthly raise, reinstatement of coal
allowances and release and rehiring of three other dismissed
Solidarity activists.
   Church sources said earlier Saturday that one of the Solidarity
activists had been freed from detention.
   Solidarity last month urged that May 1 be ``a day of protest''
against the nationwide price increases that have raised prices 42
percent in the first three months of 1988.
   Union activists applied for permission to march Sunday in Warsaw
but were turned down.
   However, opposiiton sources said the march was planned anyway.
</TEXT>
