<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TestBanTest 1stLd-Writethru a0558 04-30 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Test Ban Test, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0558,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Soviet Scientists Claim Success In Detecting Simulated Nuke
Blasts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with two grafs to UPDATE with Saturday's test;
picks up 4th graf pvs, ``The experiment ...'' INSERTS graf after
6th graf pvs, ``Archambeau heads ...,'' to UPDATE with timing and
locations of three explosions; picks up 7th graf pvs, ``The blasts
were ...'' SUBS 11th to 13th grafs with three grafs to UPDATE with
recordings of three explosions and DELETE details of detection of
first blast; picks up 14th graf pvs, ``This is about ...''
^LaserPhoto Staffing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEEP SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fault-riddled rock layers under
the Nevada desert blur and diminish shock waves from underground
explosions, but weekend tests showed cheating under a nuclear test
ban still could be detected, scientists said.
   Experiments using buried charges of conventional explosive and a
network of sensitive instruments proved that even the smallest
explosions can be monitored, said research geophysicist Holly
Eissler.
   Ms. Eissler, of the University of California San Diego, was part
of a team from the Natural Resources Defense Council that set up
modified earthquake-monitoring equipment to record shock waves from
three detonations of TNT in remote areas of Nevada Friday and
Saturday.
   The third and largest test Saturday showed clearly on seismic
equipment here, producing cheers from scientists. The first test
Friday was less obvious and a second one later Friday showed up on
only the most sophisticated instruments, Ms. Eissler said.
   ``The experiment is successful,'' Charles Archambeau, a
University of Colorado-Boulder geophysics professor, said after
seismometers detected the first detonation of 10 tons of TNT on
Friday.
   ``It means that we can more accurately gauge the numbers and
distribution of stations that will be required to verify a
low-threshold treaty. It also will help us to set the threshold of
what's verifiable,'' he said.
   Archambeau heads the seismic monitoring advisory committee of
the Natural Resources Defense Council, a private group conducting
the experiments in this country and the Soviet Union in cooperation
with the Soviet Academy of Sciences.
   Following the explosion of 10 tons of TNT buried beneath the
desert 100 miles north of Reno and another 10-ton shot 50 miles
south of the Nevada Test Site on Friday, a 15-ton detonation was
set off Saturday about 100 miles east of Carson City and 210 miles
northeast of Deep Springs.
   The blasts were monitored by Soviet and American equipment here
in the Sierra Nevada about midway between Reno and Las Vegas and at
two permanent Defense Council installations closer to the Nevada
Test Site 110 miles north of Las Vegas, where all U.S. underground
nuclear detonations are conducted. An additional 140 temporary
monitoring stations were set up across Nevada.
   Experiments similar to this weekend's were conducted by the
Soviet and American scientists last September near the Soviet test
site in Kazakhstan.
   Because of the geology of the Soviet Union, the readings there
were much more pronounced than those so far in the fractured
foundations of Nevada.
   ``It was a very small signal, but it was a discernible signal,''
Ms. Eissler said of Friday's first test. She noted that a limited
nuclear test ban treaty passed Thursday by the House forbids
detonations larger than one kiloton, 100 times the strength of the
10-ton TNT blast.
   She said Friday's first test was recorded here at about three
times normal background noise, and the second explosion was barely
detectable.
   Saturday's larger explosion registered about 10 times background
noise, Ms. Eissler said.
   The scientists initially thought Friday's first detonation
failed to register on any of the seismic monitors, but a more
detailed study indicated the test was recorded successfully 100
seconds after the blast.
   ``This is about the size we'd expect in this terrain,''
Archambeau said. He called Nevada's complex geology ``a worst-case
situation (that) will help us design networks that can do
verification in these rather difficult areas.''
   The experiments are expected to show that ``any chances for
cheating are about excluded'' under a test ban, said Evgeni
Velikhov, vice president of the Soviet Academy and an adviser to
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   ``We think the comprehensive test ban is very important,'' he
added. ``It is extremely important to stop the arms race.''
   The testing equipment was designed ``to feel the difference
between nuclear and industrial explosions and ... very small
earthquakes,'' according to Thomas Cochran, senior staff scientist
for the Defense Council.
</TEXT>
