<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0572,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede CLEVELAND</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Warns Supporters Against Overconfidence</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 10 grafs new to UPDATE with Dukakis responding to
Jackson, Bush criticisms; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng, `The
Massachusetts.' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis responded to
criticism from Republican George Bush on Saturday, saying ``I think
maybe it's time for him to stop criticizing others,'' and defended
his leadership ability against rival Jesse Jackson's sharpened
charges.
   Dukakis, the Democratic presidential front-runner, answered the
increasing criticism from his competitors only when questioned by
reporters. He had avoided any mention of his rivals during a day of
campaigning in two states.
   The Massachusetts governor pointed to his state's economic
record in trying to deflect Jackson's suggestion that Dukakis was
offering only a managerial approach to governing and lacked the
leadership abilities that he provides.
   ``When it comes to leadership, I'm very proud of the fact that
I'm governor of a state which is generally viewed to be a state
that's way out front,'' Dukakis said. ``My kind of leadership is as
a doer, and not a talker.''
   Dukakis has also come under fire from Bush, who a day earlier
charged Dukakis with ``waffling all over the field'' in his
reaction to the administration's decision to attack Iranian
positions in the Persian Gulf. He was asked about Bush's comments
that he has ``cannon fodder'' to use against Dukakis in the fall,
suggesting it was some unknown evidence from the governor's
administration in Massachusetts.
   ``I really don't think the American people are interested in
what George Bush thinks of me and I think of him and whether he's
got cannon fodder or whatever it is that he's got,'' Dukakis said.
   ``I think maybe it's time for him to stop criticizing others and
to begin to address some fundamental issues that face this
country,'' Dukakis said.
   Running with a big delegate lead and confident of his standing
in the remaining primaries, Dukakis has campaigned cautiously and
strived to avoid the suggestion of acrimony.
   His campaign schedule has been carried out in a manner that has
limited his availability to take questions, while he has delivered
speeches repeating familiar themes and exhorting supporters not to
become overconfident.
   Earlier in Ohio, Dukakis told supporters they must take ``this
primary seriously.''
   The Massachusetts governor took an early morning stroll through
an outdoor fruit market in downtown Cincinnati and later spoke to
union members at a half-empty labor hall in Cleveland less than an
hour after Jackson received an enthusiastic response for his speech
before the same group.
   Dukakis also spoke to a largely black group in Cleveland. He
criticized the Reagan administration's anti-drug efforts and told
them his aim was ``to open up that door of opportunity to all
citizens, no matter who they are or where they come from or what
the color of their skin.''
   ``That's really what this campaign is all about,'' he said.
   He traveled to Indianapolis where he attended the state
Democratic Party's annual Jefferson-Jackson dinner and planned to
visit a high school prom where aides said he would deliver a
message on the dangers of drinking and driving.
   With a large and growing lead in delegates over Jackson, and a
primary calender strongly in his favor, Dukakis has been urging
supporters at every stop to ignore the polls and work to produce a
large turnout.
   Standing amid new sofas and tables on the loading dock of a
Cincinnati furniture store, Dukakis spoke optimistically of winning
the nomination but also urged them not to become complacent.
   ``I want to ask you once again to do everything you can, on
those phone banks, in your neighborhoods, with your friends and
co-workers, to make sure the people are taking this primary
seriously, that they know it is important,'' he said.
   ``If we work together ... we're going to win in Ohio, we're
going to win in Indiana ... and we're going to win this
nomination,'' he said.
   In urging his voters to turn out on Tuesday, Dukakis repeatedly
referred to his own 1978 re-election defeat in Massachusetts
despite a one-time lead in the polls.
   ``It was the most painful experience of my life,'' he told union
members in Cleveland.
   He compared the experience to being a worker laid off from his
job, although he added that in his case it was his own fault. ``I
know what it's like,'' he said.
</TEXT>
