<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CableTV 1stLd-Writethru a0513 04-30 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cable TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cable TV Industry Enjoying Good Times, But Warning Signs Ahead</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf to CORRECT Metzenbaum's designation to senator
sted of representative; changes time element to March sted of last
month.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Times are good for cable television. It has
become a $12 billion industry whose programming is watched in more
than half of all American households, and subscribership is
continuing to grow.
   But the industry is also wary of how long this prosperity will
last.
   Cable TV is no longer a highly regulated industry weighted down
with debt from stringing cable to build community systems. Most of
the systems are built and cable operators have more control than
ever over what viewers see and how much they pay.
   ``It's a very healthy industry; it's never been healthier,''
said Edward Hatch, a media analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets in New York. ``Life is good in the cable industry right
now.''
   But some in Congress think it may be too good. Lawmakers,
prompted by complaints from constituents about rate increases and
poor service and the competitive concerns of others in the
entertainment industry, have raised the specter of reregulating the
cable industry.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, fired a warning shot at the
industry at a congressional hearing in March, saying ``some of us
feel we were had'' by a law that freed most cable companies of
municipal rate control in January 1987. He and other lawmakers
wonder aloud whether cable has become an unregulated monopoly.
   The threat from Capitol Hill ``is a concern you can't ignore,''
Hatch said, and this and other regulatory issues are on the minds
of cable operators attending their industry's annual convention
here this week.
   More than 13,000 people were expected to attend the National
Cable Television Association convention, which runs from Sunday
through Tuesday.
   Cable TV systems added more than 4 million subscribers in 1987,
putting the households receiving cable at 51 percent _ about 45
million.
   Now that many of cable operators have finished building their
systems _ wiring more than 80 percent of American households _
cable companies are beginning to pay off their debt and have cash
to spend on programming.
   Cable is looking to programming to attract new subscribers, and
the industry is encouraged by the success of efforts like
Showtime's critically acclaimed ``It's Garry Shandling's Show,'' a
series that now also airs on the Fox broadcasting network.
   Home Box Office's ``Dear America: Letters Home from Vietnam''
also received high marks from TV critics, and the Entertainment and
Sports Programming Network, ESPN, has landed some big sports
contracts, including National Football League games.
   ``Things are going extraordinarily well for cable,'' said Robert
Alter, president of the Cabletelevision Advertising Bureau.
``People are discovering the choice in programming that cable
offers.''
   Cable systems are adding subscribers at the rate of 1 percent to
2 percent a year, and those with the wire are spending nearly as
much time watching programming produced by cable as they do viewing
programs of the three major broadcast networks, he said.
   Increased viewership boosted cable advertising sales above the
$1 billion mark last year, and ad revenues are expected to hit $1.5
billion this year, he said. Each new subscriber is worth about
$2,000 to the asset value of many cable systems, he said.
   ``There is a tremendous incentive on cable to sharpen its
marketing skills to build its subscriber base,'' he said.
   Rates have also risen since deregulation 16 months ago, and that
has concerned Congress. Metzenbaum says prices in some systems have
risen by up to 400 percent.
   The NCTA, however, says the average cable subscriber's monthly
bill rose 6.7 percent in the first six months after deregulation.
While basic service prices rose about 10.6 percent, rates for
premium or pay channels like HBO dropped 2.5 percent, according to
the study.
</TEXT>
