<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 2041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CityResignations     04-30 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-City Resignations,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Who Used City Funds to Pay Rent and Food Bills Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the District of Columbia's
Department of Human Services and two aides have resigned after
reports surfaced that the three used city funds to pay their rent
and food bills, officials said Saturday.
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr. demanded the resignations Friday night
after meeting with the city administrator and legal counsel,
according to John White, a spokesman for the mayor.
   Director M. Jerome Woods and Chief Deputy Theodore Carthen had
been living in an $875-a-month, two-bedroom apartment using city
housing allowance funds and receiving some reimbursements for food
since August. Steve Y'Barra and a fourth assistant, Deputy Director
Robert Little, were also found to be living off city funds.
   Little's resignation was not immediately accepted pending
determination of whether he is responsible for the housing
allowances he received.
   None has been charged with criminal wrongdoing, White said.
   City personnel regulations allow the reimbursement of housing
and food costs to out-of-town employees hired as experts if the
employees are not on a regular work schedule.
   The impropriety, however, stems from the fact that all four men
receive pay for normal 40-hour work weeks, although they maintain
residences in other states, according to White.
   Neither Woods, who assumed the position in July, nor Carthen
could be reached for comment Saturday.
   A total of 11 people, including two deputy mayors, have been
convicted of criminal wrongdoing while serving in the nine-year-old
Barry administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
