<HEAD>Bomb Explodes at Opposition Labor Union; Guerrillas Blamed For Six
Killings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded at the
headquarters of an opposition labor union Saturday, damaging the
front of the building, shattering windows and injuring a woman with
flying glass, a union leader said.
   In other developments, authorities found the bodies of six
people on a ranch near the capital and blamed the killings on
leftist guerrillas. In the eastern city of San Miguel a university
official said soldiers destroyed the stage for a music festival and
beat several organizers.
   No one claimed responsibility for the explosion at the National
Salvadoran Workers Union, in the northeastern part of the capital.
   Union leader Humberto Centeno said the woman, who lives nearby,
suffered minor injuries, he said.
   Centeno blamed the attack on supporters of President Jose
Napoleon Duarte. He said he believed Duarte's U.S.-backed centrist
government was trying to intimidate the union on the eve of a march
by 50,000 workers planned for Sunday, the country's labor day.
   In San Miguel, soldiers destroyed the stage the music festival,
surrounded a hotel where foreign artists were staying and beat
several organizers of the event and workers building the stage,
University of El Salvador rector Luis Argueta Antillon said
Saturday.
   He called the action ``an act of terrorism.''
   The festival, called ``A Song for Peace with Sovereignty and
Independence in El Salvador,'' began Wednesday in the San Miguel
square. On Saturday, the last day of the festival, the performances
took place in San Salvador as planned, in a plaza across from the
Metropolitan Cathedral.
   Among the artists were American singer and composer Holly Near;
the U.S. group ``Human Condition,'' a Venezuelan group and several
Salvadoran groups.
   San Miguel is about 85 miles east of San Salvador.
   The armed forces blamed guerrillas for the deaths of four women
and two men whose bodies were found Friday night on a ranch near
Santa Ana, 40 miles from San Salvador.
   A military source in the area said the peasants were taken from
their homes Thursday by men in olive green uniforms and fatally
shot.
   A red cloth with FPL-FMLN, initials of the Popular Liberation
Forces of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, was found
on one of the victims, said the source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The front is the umbrella organization for five leftist
guerrilla groups fighting to overthrow the government.
   In April, 72 rebels were killed and 47 wounded in combat, the
armed forces said Saturday. It said 41 soldiers were killed and 76
wounded.
   The report blamed the rebels for the deaths of 41 campesinos. It
said the rebels wounded 11 others and kidnapped 41 civilians during
the month.
   Nearly 65,000 people have died in the 8-year-old war, the
majority of them civilians, according to human rights organizations.
</TEXT>
