<HEAD>Round of Cease-Fire Talks End, More Arrests Outside Union Hall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New info-changes grafs 1-8, both sides far apart, can't agree
on when or where next talks to be held. Pick up 4th graf pvs: The
rebel delegation got rid...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and rebel leaders on
Saturday ended their second round of discussions with both sides
far apart on an agreement for a lasting cease-fire.
   The Sandinistas and rebels, known as Contras, gave conflicting
accounts of progress.
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega, head of the Sandinista
delegation, said after the meeting ended at 7 p.m. EDT that ``some
progress'' had been made. He said the two sides agreed on 16 of 32
proposals made by the government.
   Ortega gave no details. The Sandinistas said the negotiators had
tentatively agreed to meet again May 12-14, but the place has not
been determined.
   Contra spokesman Aristides Sanchez told a news conference there
had been no agreement on when the next session will be held and he
said the rebels did not want the talks to resume in Managua
``because the climate is not good here.''
   He said the rebels refused to sign a joint communique the
Sandinistas had prepared on what was achieved during the last
session.
   Meanwhile, police arrested three more people outside a union
hall were 38 workers were in the sixth day of a hunger strike
demanding higher wages.
   The government and rebel leaders met behind closed doors at a
Managua hotel in the third and final day of talks to work out
details of the March 23 cease-fire pact.
   The rebel delegation got rid of one of the major stumbling
blocks when it agreed to withdraw its demand that combatants be
allowed to replace damaged weapons and spent ammunition while they
are in special zones.
   A Sandinista proposal calls for the rebels to move into seven
zones. Once they are concentrated in the areas, the government is
to release about 700 political prisoners and allow rebel delegates
to take part in national talks with political parties.
   The Contras on Friday rejected a Sandinista proposal that the
International Red Cross, seen here as sympathizing with the
government, immediately resupply the rebels. The cease-fire pact
called for delivery of food, clothes and medicine to the Contra
combatants only after they entered the zones.
   Contras say they want to select the organization that will send
the goods. The rebels agreed in the pact to accept only non-lethal
supplies from a neutral organization.
   Sandinista police, meanwhile, cordoned off the entrance to the
General Workers Federation, an umbrella group of anti-government
unions and the scene of demonstrations on Friday.
   About 1,500 construction workers and car mechanics walked off
their jobs Feb. 25 to demand higher salaries and protest economic
measures enacted a week earlier.
   Union officials and witnesses said the Interior Ministry's
Special Forces, known as ``black berets,'' used rubber truncheons
to break up demonstrations outside the union headquarters. Inside,
38 workers were staging the hunger strike.
   Witnesses said two men and a woman were taken into police
custody Saturday morning for gathering outside the building.
   Police scuffled with the two men and then roughly tossed them
into a pickup truck, the witnesses said.
   Barricada, the newspaper of the ruling Sandinista National
Liberation Front, reported Saturday that police detained 25 people
during the demonstrations. Eleven others were taken into custody
earlier in the week.
   The newspaper also reported an altercation between Interior
Minister Tomas Borge and Jose Castillo Osejo, director of
anti-Sandinista Radio Corporation.
   Castillo told The Associated Press he was summoned to Borge's
office Friday for allegedly reporting erroneous information about
the strike. The minister punched him in the mouth, Castillo said.
   Barricada reported that Castillo insulted Borge when the two met
in private.
   ``As a result of the incident, Castillo suffered minor
injuries,'' it said.
</TEXT>
