<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0621,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Brewing In The West</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf ``In the South'' with two grafs to UPDATE with
details of Florida storm. Picks up 7th graf pvs ``Elsewhere,
showers''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold air moving into the Northwest triggered showers Saturday
while a storm system developed over the central Rockies, and
thunderstorms were scattered over the South.
   Showers were scattered along the coast of Oregon and northern
California and over central Montana and northwestern Utah.
   Snow showers spread over the Oregon Cascades, with near-zero
visibility reported at Sexton Summit. An advisory for 6 or more
inches of snow was posted and snow also developed in sections of
the Sierra Nevada range in northern California.
   The developing storm system produced gusty wind over southern
California's mountains and desert areas with gusts to 50 mph
reported over the mountains and gusts to 45 mph were clocked in the
desert. Wind speeds were increasing across the mountains and
northern parts of Arizona.
   Snow advisories were posted into early Sunday for the mountains
and foothills of Montana and for far western Wyoming. A winter
storm watch was posted into Sunday for Wyoming's Big Horn and Wind
River mountains.
   In the South, showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the
central Gulf Coast region through much of Florida. Strong
thunderstorm wind caused about $100,000 damage to 15 to 20 trailer
homes in Venice, Fla., police Lt. Jim Hanks said.
   In Boca Raton, Fla., wind threw a car 50 feet, damaged several
homes, snapped power lines and blew windows out of stores and cars,
authorities said.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered across New England with
thunderstorms from northern New Jersey into southeastern New York
state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at Truckee, Calif., to 90 at Laredo, Texas, and Chandler,
Ariz. The low for the day was 18 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, showers were forecast from the Northwest into the
high Plains, with thunderstorms scattered into North Dakota. Snow,
possibly heavy at times, was forecast at higher elevations of the
northern Rockies from Montana into Wyoming, and over the northern
mountains of Arizona. Thunderstorms were forecast over much of the
Florida Peninsula, with scattered rain across New England.
   Highs only in the middle to upper 40s were predicted in parts of
the inland Northwest; in the 50s across the Pacific Northwest
through a small area of southern Nevada, central Arizona and
eastern Utah into eastern Montana, and from the eastern Great Lakes
through New England; in the 80s from southern New Mexico through
the southern Plains and eastern Texas; in the low to mid 90s across
west-central Texas into the central Rio Grande Valley; and in the
60s or 70s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
