<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SubmarineFire 1stLd-Writethru a0615 04-30 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Submarine Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0615,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Pauses To Honor Sailors Killed In Submarine Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``A funeral'' to UPDATE with scheduled funeral
taking place.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three sailors who were killed when an
explosion and fire filled the submarine USS Bonefish with dense
smoke and toxic gas were remembered Saturday as men who knew the
cost of freedom.
   About 500 people gathered for a memorial service for the three
who died in the accident in the conventionally powered boat off the
Florida coast six days earlier.
   ``We loved these three valiant men,'' said Capt. James
Rutherford of Submarine Group Six, to which the Bonefish belonged.
``Thank you God for men like them who know the price of liberty.''
   The accident killed Lt. Ray Everts, 30, of Naoma, W.Va.; Petty
Officer 1st Class Robert W. Bordelon Jr., 39; of Willis, Texas; and
Petty Officer 3rd Class Marshall T. Lindgren, 21, of Pisgah Forest,
N.C.
   A funeral for Bordelon was held Saturday in Conroe, Texas, and
services for the other two victims will be held Sunday. Lindgren's
mother and brother attended the memorial at St. Michaels Lutheran
Church on the edge of Charleston's historic district, said Lt.
Cmdr. John Tull, a spokesman for the Charleston Naval Base.
   Twenty-two other members of the 92-man crew of the
diesel-electric submarine were injured, most by smoke inhalation.
The Bonefish was towed back to the Charleston Naval Base on Friday.
   While most of the Navy personnel in the congregation wore their
summer white uniforms, the Bonefish crew dressed in their somber
winter blues.
   ``It is all the men of the Bonefish we honor today,'' said Vice
Adm. Daniel Cooper, commander of the Atlantic Fleet submarine
forces.
   ``The miracle is that 89 men were rescued and the ship returned
to port through the heroic, professional and unselfish acts of
others,'' he added.
   Rear Adm. William Owens, commander of Submarine Group Six,
praised the crew of the Bonefish, saying ``the spirit and the
substance of these people is something that I will always
remember.''
   Navy Chaplain Lt. Cmdr. Raymond Michener said the Navy family
has suffered a loss.
   ``All of us gathered here are in a very real sense one large
family. We are brought together by nothing else than the sea,'' he
said.
   The Bonefish was on a training exercise when it was struck by
the explosion and fire in a battery compartment. It was submerged
at periscope depth at the time, and the crew quickly surfaced the
vessel and evacuated to other Navy ships.
   There's no timetable for completion of the investigation of the
mishap, Tull said.
</TEXT>
