<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Women-QueenMother     04-30 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Queen Mother,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Workers of World War II Meet With Queen Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of women who served in the
``Land Army'' that kept British agriculture going during World War
II gathered Saturday with Queen Mother Elizabeth to share memories.
   ``All of us are a little older _ and perhaps a little wiser _
than in those wartime days,'' the 87-year-old former queen told the
gathering of 560 women at the Grand Hotel.
   ``But I know the same spirit of good comradeship, loyalty and
devotion to queen and country remains just the same,'' said the
queen mother, whose daughter is Queen Elizabeth II.
   ``The King and I were proud and grateful to you all for your
great contribution to the war effort,'' she said, referring to her
late husband, King George VI.
   The women thronged around her, cheering and waving until a path
was cleared for her by officers of Scotland Yard's Special Branch
who guard the royal family and government.
   At its height, more than 90,000 women belonged to the ``Land
Army,'' taking over the farm and forestry jobs left empty when the
men went to fight.
   Land Army chairman Jean Proctor, told the queen mother: ``At the
time of our service you were our queen and none of us can forget
your concern for our welfare.''
   It was a final national reunion of the British Women's Land Army
Society, but local reunions will continue.
</TEXT>
