<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonDeath     04-30 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Death,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Murderer An Apparent Suicide After Escape Plans Foiled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POLK CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of contracting his wife's
murder through an advertisement in Soldier of Fortune magazine was
found hanging in his prison cell Saturday, an apparent suicide,
authorities said.
   Robert Spearman, who was serving a sentence of life plus 20
years in the 1985 slaying of his wife, was found dead three days
after authorities announced they had thwarted a planned helicopter
escape.
   The body of Spearman, 60, was found hanging by a bedsheet from
the top bars of his cell wall in Polk County Correctional Center in
this town about 35 miles northeast of Tampa, said state corrections
spokesman Bob Macmaster. Spearman was found Saturday morning just
15 minutes after the last check of his cell, Macmaster said.
   Macmaster said Spearman was not considered a suicide risk.
   Spearman had been transferred to the Polk prison Monday from
Zephyrhills Correctional Institution, 25 miles to the east.
   On Wednesday, the Florida Department of Law Enforcement
disclosed that agents had thwarted an attempt by Spearman, a
millionaire boatyard owner from Palm Beach Gardens, to arrange a
helicopter escape from Zephryrhills.
   Two undercover FDLE agents posing as pilots received $4,700 as a
down payment on a $54,700 contract to steal a helicopter and fly
Spearman out of the prison, said Ed Williams, agent in charge of
the FDLE's Tampa office.
   Spearman asked the undercover agents to have two machine guns
and four hand grenades aboard the helicopter, authorities said. He
intended to use the grenades to kill his prosecutor, Palm Beach
County Assistant State Attorney Moria Lasch, said John Joyce, an
FDLE spokesman in Tallahassee.
   Spearman was charged with attempted escape and weapons offenses.
Stepson Fred Douglas Laurent Jr. of Fort Lauderdale, a suspected
accomplice, was charged with the same offenses but remains at
large, authorities said.
   Longtime friend Gene Fenno said Spearman was struggling to cope
with prison life when he visited him last summer.
   ``He was always talking about getting out, that he couldn't
stand it,'' Fenno said after the escape plan was disclosed.
   Attorney David Roth, who represented Spearman in his murder
trial, said he was not shocked by the escape plan because under the
sentence imposed in April 1987, he would not be eligible for parole
before he reached his mid-80s.
   ``Someone in his position would not have a great deal to lose,''
Roth said.
   Spearman was convicted of hiring two men who had advertised in
Soldier of Fortune to kill his wife, Anita, for $20,000. She was
bludgeoned to death in November 1985.
   Prosecutors said Spearman wanted to get rid of his
cancer-stricken wife, a former West Palm Beach assistant city
manager, because he had fallen in love with his secretary and
didn't want a costly divorce.
</TEXT>
