<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OilSpill     04-30 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Crude Flushed Into Open, Easing Part of Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wildlife casualty toll from a
175,000-gallon oil spill 40 miles northeast of San Francisco
appeared to have peaked Friday, and gusty winds and high tides
helped the cleanup, officials said.
   ``They aren't picking up many more birds at all now, and we
don't expect to get too many more at all,'' said Coast Guard Lt.
Bob Brach.
   Rescuers have recovered about 470 oil-soaked birds and animals
since a Shell Oil Co. refinery spilled crude oil into the Peyton
Slough on April 23, said Chuck Monroe, regional patrol chief for
the state Fish and Game Department. Of those, about 200 have died
or were found dead, he said.
   Only about a dozen oily birds were brought to the International
Bird Rescue Center in Berkeley on Friday, said spokeswoman Beth
Podvin.
   For the second consecutive day, wind and high tides pushed about
1,500 gallons of oil from remote inlets where it had been trapped
into open water and marshland.
   Although the spread could threaten other coastal wildlife
sanctuaries, it helped the cleanup, authorities said.
   ``More and more oil is getting flushed from the marshy areas
into the (Carquinez) Strait, but that's actually working for the
most part to our advantage because it's making it easier to pick
up,'' said Todd Nelson of the Coast Guard.
   Eight skimmer boats removed several oil-sheen patches over a
12-mile section of the strait, Brach said. More winds and high
tides were expected to continue pushing oil into the strait over
the weekend, he added.
   The crude also has begun to thicken, turning into tar and making
cleanup along shorelines easier, Coast Guard officials said. About
126,000 gallons of the thick crude has been recovered so far, they
said.
   The spill occurred after a pipe used to draw off rainwater broke
inside a Shell oil tank, allowing crude to be siphoned out, Shell
said.
   The company acknowledged the practice of keeping outtake valves
open during storms violated federal regulations.
   Larry Kolb, principal engineer fo the state Regional Water
Quality Control Board, has estimated the spill could cost Shell $4
million, including $3 million in penalties.
</TEXT>
