<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Mengistu,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mengistu Blames Africa's Internal Struggles On Outside Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Africa's limited resources are
being exhausted by wars with groups supported by enemies of Africa,
President Mengistu Haile Mariam said Friday.
   ``Some external forces inimical to Africa have posed obstacles
compelling African states to divert their resources and effort away
from socio-economic development,'' Mengistu said at a ceremony
marking the 30th anniversary of the U.N. Economic Commission for
Africa, which has headquarters in Addis Ababa.
   Mengistu did not name the outside enemies he held responsible
for Africa's internal struggles, but said they ``are challenging
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of African states. Africa
should in one voice, strongly condemn them and tell them, hands off
our continent.''
   His Soviet-backed Marxist government is fighting rebel groups in
Ethiopia's northernmost provinces of Eritrea and Tigre.
   Eritrea has Africa's longest civil war, a 27-year secessionist
fight by the Eritrean People's Liberation Front. In Tigre, south of
Eritrea, the Tigre People's Liberation Front has been fighting for
14 years.
   Mengistu's government refers to the guerrillas as bandits.
</TEXT>
