<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthInsurance     04-30 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Insurance,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Federal Health Insurance Plan Criticized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal employees' health insurance
program is inefficient, overpriced and offers inadequate coverage
to its 10 million beneficiaries, according to a report presented to
the government Friday.
   The Washington Post said in Saturday's editions that the report
to the Office of Personnel Management found that the health plan
costs $785 million more than it should for the benefits it provides
and will only get worse unless changed.
   ``With our huge number of employees, we should be able to get a
really good deal,'' said OPM Director Constance Horner. ``We don't
have a really good deal.''
   The report on the Federal Employee Health Benefits Program _
which covers federal workers, retirees and their dependents _ was
prepared by the consulting firm of Towers, Perrin, Forster &
Crosby. The 28-year-old benefits program has grown to include 480
health plans.
   The consultants found that those plans compete to attract the
healthy and avoid the sick, rather than competing to offer the best
benefits at the cheapest rates.
   The need to attract the healthiest workers means ``no plan can
offer high levels of coverage in certain critical areas'' such as
mental health, drug abuse or nursing care, the consultants found.
</TEXT>
