<1ST_LINE>s a BC-StairMinistry Adv01   04-30 1172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Stair Ministry, Adv 01,1209</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Allegations about Christian Community Denied by Evangelist</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALTERBORO, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heading north out of town past farms and
pine stands, one might never notice the Overcomer Campground _
until recently, when television news vans began clustering at the
headquarters of evangelist R.G. Stair's ministry.
   The attention follows reports by families in the Philadelphia
area that their children have abandoned their lives for a Christian
cult, and their allegations that cult members can't leave because
Stair controls their money.
   The allegations are denied by Stair, a 51-year-old Pennsylvania
native who, like other members of the Faith Cathedral Fellowship,
lives in a renovated mobile home set among the tall oaks and pines
near this town about 50 miles from Charleston.
   ``We have a good lifestyle here,'' he said. ``We believe in the
Christian principle of having food and raiment, be content.''
   The ministry is headquartered in a nondescript brown-roofed
motel building along U.S. 15. Beside it is a modest brown building,
which is the congregation's tabernacle.
   Worshippers sit on folding white wood chairs each Friday evening
and Saturday morning to hear Stair's sermons of Bible prophecy
delivered from a podium on a red-carpeted riser. Behind the podium
is a small room in which the evangelist records his radio programs
carried on 50 stations nationwide.
   A few miles farther north is the sect's 74-acre farm, where 37
people are busy farming and renovating house trailers.
   The farm has a five-acre plot where residents raise everything
from turnips to squash and watermelon. Nearby are a kitchen and
dining hall where residents gather for prayers and share their
meals.
   Despite the allegations the group espouses survivalism, there's
no indication of any weapons or military dress among the residents
of the ministry, where a sign requests there be ``No Smoking, No
Drinking and No Swearing.''
   A number have their own bank accounts and vehicles. There is no
fence, but a free-standing gate at the motel keeps cars from
swerving into the parking lot at night.
   Visitors can stay without charge, but there are some
requirements for those who want to stay permanently, Stair said.
   ``We want to make sure they believe in the Christian faith like
we do,'' he said.
   They must also be debt-free, because ``it's not right for me to
take other people's money and pay your debts,'' he added.
   The ministry takes in about $30,000 a month, Stair said, adding
he pays about $20,000 monthly for radio air time. Since the
challenges to his ministry were raised, several stations have taken
the fiery Overcomer broadcast off the air.
   Stair has predicted that President Reagan won't complete his
term in office, there'll be an economic shakeup beginning next
month and there'll be a limited nuclear war before the year is out.
   ``I believe God speaks to me,'' he said in a broadcast prepared
for this weekend. ``That's one of the issues they have taken up
with me. But how many of you Christians out there in radio land
believe God speaks to you?''
   Stair said the religious community is not a survivalist enclave,
noting ``we've got a Navy base over there (in Charleston) with
submarines. If they're going to blow us up, they're going to blow
us up. There is no human protection from a nuclear war.''
   The sect does have a food storehouse, stocked with several
thousand pounds of food. It's for the congregation's use and is
also given away to the needy.
   Stair, who is called Brother Stair by the congregation, was
ordained a Methodist minister. Now, he said, ``I won't identify
with any organized religion. I just call myself a Christian.''
   He said the Lord told him to move South 30 years ago ``because
the safest place for Christians in the end time is going to be the
South.'' He has lived in Walterboro for 10 years.
   Much of the recent controversy has centered on the move of Gerry
and Linda McCourt of Drexel Hill, Pa., to the community.
   Gloria Ahern, Mrs. McCourt's mother, said Stair's prophecy of a
nuclear war inspired them to quickly sell their home and belongings
and head to South Carolina.
   She and others in the Philadelphia area have called for
investigations by the IRS and the FBI.
   But Mrs. McCourt said, ``We just wanted to move to a quieter
place.''
   She said the couple had planned to sell their house and, when a
buyer offered them $60,000 cash, they decided to take it. Real
estate agents had earlier offered to list the house for $74,000 and
$65,000, she said.
   Mrs. McCourt, who is expecting her second child in June, said
she leads a different life from her mother. She said she and her
husband don't watch television or go to movies and on vacations
were likely to go to Christian retreats.
   She said when she arrived in South Carolina, she called home to
let her mother know where the family was.
   ``All she kept saying was, `You're sick,''' she said. ``There
was no having a conversation.''
   But Mrs. McCourt said her mother is welcome to visit. ``I wish
she would come down here. We have no malice.''
   Stair said that if his critics in Pennsylvania were to visit,
``There would be no question of whether I'm making their people
stay here or not. Whether they would still approve of the lifestyle
is a different story.''
   Gerry McCourt said the family felt it was time for a change long
before they had heard of Stair.
   ``We wanted something more out in the country, a slower way of
life,'' he added.
   In Pennsylvania their church group ate together and had church
five times a week, so ``our lifestyle hasn't changed that much
except we lived in the suburbs and we might have had a little bit
more,'' he said.
   Dave Moratto, another member of the Walterboro congregation,
worked for a livestock dealer in Florida for 25 years before coming
to South Carolina last summer.
   ``I feel this is where the Lord would have me to be,'' he said
as he cleaned turnips in a sink outside the group kitchen. ``People
do it every day in Florida _ sell what they have and move about.''
   Shirley Roe, who originally came from Austin, Texas, said she
and her husband and son were living in a Volkswagen bus in North
Dakota last winter when they decided to come to Walterboro.
   ``We'd been seeking the Lord's will. He was telling us his will
by telling us to come here,'' she said as she helped prepare dinner.
   Chief Deputy R.F. Stevens of the Colleton County Sheriff's
Department said that in recent weeks, the department had received a
number of calls from relatives of members of the community.
   ``We try to contact them and tell them to call home,'' he said.
   ``We have no indication of wrongdoing,'' he said, adding, ``It's
just a situation that bears watching.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 1</NOTE>
