<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 0609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     04-30 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Down Then Up, Ends Largely Unchanged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices sagged then bounced back in
nervous trading that reflected the uncertain outcome of a key OPEC
meeting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, a sensitive barometer of
price trends, traders remained wary Friday of guessing results of
the meeting of Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
ministers in Vienna, Austria.
   The ministers were trying to develop a strategy to jointly
reduce output with eight non-OPEC producers in order to erase
excess supplies from the market.
   Contracts for June delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, closed 1 cent higher at $17.99 per 42-gallon
barrel Friday, after having been down as much as 43 cents.
   Among refined products, wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 0.16
cent per gallon to 51.67 cents, and wholesale heating oil rose 0.82
cent a gallon to 51.79 cents.
   James Steel, a strategist at the Refco Inc. commodities firm,
said oil prices dropped sharply early in the session because of
what he called carryover selling from Thursday over the lack of
significant news from the OPEC meeting.
   After prices fell so quickly, some traders saw buying
opportunities and the market quickly moved up. That prompted other
traders who had sold borrowed oil on the hunch prices would fall to
buy it back, a price-boosting influence known as short-covering.
   Donald Morton, an analyst at the Boston office of
Prudential-Bache Securities, Inc., called the late-session
bounceback a ``pre-weekend, short-covering rally.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
